Commentary.Commentary: We are ready for the Kiwis' reply! Tom Latham and Will Young walk out to bat. Umesh Yadav has the ball in hand. Here we go...

Now, New Zealand have to bat really well. The wicket is not easy, it is turning and turning sharply. It is going to take a big effort from their batters if they are to get close to India's first innings score. India, on the other hand, would want a good lead but first they would love a couple of wickets before Tea. Stay tuned for New Zealand's reply in a bit.

The New Zealand bowling was just about one man, Ajaz Patel. The rest were quite under par. Especially William Somerville and Kyle Jamieson. Tim Southee too bowled his heart out. He did not get a wicket but kept it nice and tight. However, had the left-arm spinner got some support, India may well have ended below 250. A marathon effort though from Ajaz Patel. A moment he will never forget.

Coming to the game now, have to say, India will be pretty pleased with the total they have got. Have to say they have got a total which feels above par on this surface and they too have one man to thank and that is Mayank Agarwal. Yes, he did get support from a couple of other batters but it was his innings which could well be the difference in this game. He saw wickets fall at the other end but held fort at one. Axar Patel too played a handy role with the lower-order and the stand between the two is what took India above 300.

No matter what you're doing at the moment, just take a minute, get up and give this man a standing ovation! Absolutely sensational from Ajaz Patel. He was extremely pleased just knowing that he will be playing in Mumbai, the place where he was born but now, he would be on cloud 9, what an effort, 10 wickets in an innings is a rarity. He leads his side off the field and rightly so. A huge round of applause for him from everyone here and it is well-deserved. Take a bow.

OUT! TAKEN! HISTORY HAS BEEN MADE! Test cricket has been played since 1877 and today is only the third time that a bowler has picked up all 10 wickets in an innings! Take a bow Ajaz Patel. The man who spent his childhood in Mumbai, has written his name in golden letters in cricketing history in the very same city. Tosses this one up, on middle. Mohammed Siraj swings wildly across the line but gets a top edge. The ball is skied towards mid on, Rachin Ravindra settles under it nicely and holds onto the catch. Everyone here at the ground stands up to applaud Ajaz Patel. He joins the elite club of Jim Laker and Anil Kumble. A memorable day for Ajaz. INDIA HAVE BEEN BUNDLED OUT FOR 325!
Commentary.Howout: c Rachin Ravindra b Ajaz Patel

Commentary.Commentary: FOUR! Ajaz Patel looks for the blockhole and Mohammed Siraj looks to take him one. Siraj gets an inside edge which goes past the leg stump and into the boundary.
Around middle and leg, Siraj gets an inside edge onto the pads.
Mohammed Siraj is the last man in for India.

OUT! TAKEN! Number 9 for Ajaz Patel! What a feat this is! Second New Zealander to take 9 wickets in an innings in Tests. He has 4 balls to go in this over to take 10. Yadav looks to up the ante, he steps out but gets too close to the pitch of the ball. Still goes for the shot but hits it way too flat as he fails to get under it. It goes to long off where it is taken by the fielder.
Commentary.Howout: c Rachin Ravindra b Ajaz Patel

Commentary.Commentary: On middle, defended.
On off, Yadav looks to work it on the leg side, closes the face of the bat early, it goes off a soft leading edge towards point. No run taken.
A single as this is eased down to long on.
On middle, this is worked to mid-wicket.
On middle, defeded.

EDGY FOUR! William Somerville would have loved that to go to hand. He has had a tough time in this tour and nothing is going his way too. Outside off, Yadav looks to drive, it goes off the outside edge past the diving Ross Taylor at first slip and into the third man fence.
BEATEN! Flatter and quicker outside off, Yadav looks to cut but misses.
On middle, defended.
Umesh Yadav is the new man in.

Review time! After a long chat, Tom Latham decides to take the review for an LBW decision. There's no shot offered and certainly, no bat involved, so they directly go to Ball Tracker. The impact doesn't matter and Ball Tracker confirms that the ball is hitting top of off. The decision is reversed and Axar Patel is given OUT!

OUT! THREE REDS AND THAT IS A BRILLIANT, BRILLIANT REVIEW! Ajaz Patel has his 8th. Axar Patel can't believe he has to walk back but really good use of the technology by New Zealand. Not sure if they took it out of desperation or what but they won't care. They have got the big wicket of Axar and are now into the bowlers. This lands well outside off and turns back in. Patel looks to leave it with a stride forward but this hits his pads. An appeal but it is turned down. It is reviewed right at the end. Ball Tracker shows three reds. A really good knock from Axar. He was India's hope to get 350 but it now looks far away.
Commentary.Howout: lbw b Ajaz Patel

Commentary.Commentary: Gives it air and lands it outside off, defended.
On the fuller side outside off, Patel drives but to covers.
Shorter and on off, Patel pushes it to covers.
Outside off, left alone.
On a length this time, on off and spinning in. Jayant Yadav dabs it down towards leg gully.
On middle again and defended off the front foot.
William Somerville gives it a lot of air and bowls it gently around the pads. Jayant Yadav goes back and forth but manages to keep it out.
Tossed up, around middle and leg. Yadav defends it out.
On off, pushed towards mid off for a single by Axar Patel.
Short and wide, cut away straight to point.
FOUR! A tad bit short, around off. Jayant Yadav rocks back and cuts it behind square on off side and picks up a boundary.
On middle, defended off the front foot.
Drifting into leg stump this time and pushed towards mid on.
Full again, drifting in on middle. Jayant Yadav stays solid in defense.
Tossed up, around off and Yadav strides forward to defend.
Fuller one, on off and pushed towards short cover.
On a length around off and Axar Patel hops back to dab it down towards backward point.
Fullish ball, outside off and left alone by Patel.
Slowed up, around the off stump and Ajaz Patel makes an assured leave.
On middle, this is eased down to long on and Yadav gets to the other end.
Quicker and on middle, Yadav is solid in defense.
On middle, this is worked to mid-wicket.
A dot to end! On middle, Patel manages to keep it out.
Angled into the pads, this is worked through square leg for one.
Slightly fuller, this is whipped down to long on for one.
Another flighted ball on off, Patel keeps it onto the ground.
Floats it up on off, Patel defends it onto the ground.
This lands outside off and turns back in. Axar looks to defend, it goes off the inside edge, hits the pad but lands short of the man at short leg.

Fifty for Axar Patel! His maiden in Tests! Really good innings and it comes at an important time. Can he now somehow take his side upto the 350-run mark? He gets there by stroking this full ball down to long off for one.

WIDE! This is tossed up on off, it turns back in. Jayant Yadav looks to push it on the off side but it goes off the inner half, uppishly but well wide of the bowler who dives to his right. Goes down to long on for one.
An appeal but just from the bowler! This lands on off and turns back in. Yadav looks to defend, he misses and gets hit on the pads. The fielder at short leg takes it.
A single now as this is eased down to long off.
Fuller and on middle, this is pushed back to the bowler.
Floats it up on off, Patel defends.
Tossed up, around off and inviting the drive. Jayant Yadav caresses it towards backward point.
Fuller one, on middle and kept out towards mid on.
On off and Yadav gets an inside edge onto the pads.

A round-arm delivery now, angled into middle stump. Jayant Yadav defends it off the front foot and a stifled appeal as the ball was close to the pad as well. That should have been reviewed as the replays show that it was definitely pad first and looked plumb in front.
On off and eased down towards long off for a single.
Pushed through quicker, on middle and fended away by Axar Patel.
On middle and leg, nudged towards silly mid on.
Flatter one, outside off and tapped towards the gully region.
Flighted ball, on off stump. Jayant Yadav pushes it out on the leg side.
On middle, Axar Patel drives it through mid-wicket, into that huge gap. They do come back for the third as well. Good running.

SIX! With Agarwal now gone, Axar Patel wants to get some quick runs. Nicely tossed up, on off and spinning away. Axar Patel stands tall and lofts it with the spin, all the way over the extra cover fence. 300 comes up for India.
FOUR! Short and wide, easily put away by Axar Patel. Patel hangs back and cuts it through point for a boundary.
On off and blocked out by Jayant Yadav.

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! 150 and out for Mayank Agarwal! Yet another peach of a delivery from Ajaz Patel as he tosses it up, on off and this one drifts in a bit. The ball pitches on off and grips, then turns away ever so slightly and there's extra bounce on offer as well. Mayank Agarwal looks to block it out but gets a slight feather on it as Tom Blundell takes a sharp catch behind the stumps. End of a colossal innings from Mayank Agarwal and Ajaz Patel has got 7 out of 7 now! Also, Jayant Yadav comes in at number 9.
Commentary.Howout: c Tom Blundell b Ajaz Patel

Commentary.Commentary: FOUR! Put away and yet another milestone for Mayank Agarwal as he gets to 150. Short and wide, cut away behind point and the ball races away into the fence. A third score of 150 or more for Mayank Agarwal.
On middle and blocked out by Agarwal.
Tossed up, outside off and driven towards wide mid off for a single.
Flatter one, around off and kept out well by Axar Patel.
Who will bowl from the other end? It's going to be Ajaz Patel.
Around the leg stump, flicked past short leg. Shouts of 'Catch it' but the ball goes low and quickly, off the toe of the short leg fielder.
Flighted delivery, on the pads. Mayank Agarwal pushes it out towards short mid-wicket.
On off and eased down towards long off by Patel for a single.
A bit of turn and bounce on this occasion. Tossed up, around off and spinning away from the left-hander.
Around off and well left by Patel.
Nicely tossed up, on off. Axar Patel looks to drive but gets it off the inner half on the bat towards the bowler.

We are back for the post Lunch session! The umpires are out in the middle as the New Zealand players spread out on the field. India batters, Axar Patel and Mayank Agarwal stride out as well. William Somerville has the ball in hand.
... Day 2, Session 2 ...

Kiwis once again let the advantage they got at the start of the day slip away. Once again was there no support for Ajaz who was once again the pick of the bowlers. There is enough in it for the spinners but Somerville has really not been upto the mark. New Zealand will really hope to break this stand after the break and then make quick work of the lower order. An important session coming up.

A really good fightback from India courtesy a good stand between Agarwal and Axar Patel. After losing two in two balls early on in the day, the duo have batted brilliantly and have crossed the 50-run stand. India will hope they can continue and probably get them close to 350.
On middle and this one goes on with the arm, Mayank Agarwal looks to nudge it on the leg side but gets an inside edge onto the pads. That's it for this session as the umpires call for Lunch on Day 2!
Tossed up, fuller and on middle. Axar Patel stylishly drives it down towards long on for a run.
Ajaz Patel comes back over the wicket and bowls it on off stump. Axar Patel keeps it out with ease.
Flatter one, on the pads and flicked away onto the leg side.
On leg stump, turning in and padded away by Axar Patel.

FOUR BYES! This one missed everything! Ajaz Patel comes from around the stumps and bowls it on middle stump. The ball turns back in sharply after pitching and there's extra bounce on offer as well. In the end the ball goes down the leg side and past the keeper's mitts, into the fence.
On a length, around the leg stump and padded away by Mayank Agarwal.
On the pads and flicked towards short leg.
Slightly shorter, on off and turning away. Axar Patel hops back and cuts it with the spin, through cover-point. The fielder gives chase and cuts it out as they come back for the third.
Quicker one, on off and pushed back towards the bowler.
Drifted into the pads, looking to turn it away. Axar Patel looks to work it on the leg side but misses and gets hit on the pads. The visitors appeal but nothing given, probably sliding down leg.
On the pads and turning down the leg side, Agarwal works it towards backward square leg for one.
Slowed up, around middle and leg. Patel defends it out towards short mid-wicket.
On middle and leg, nudged onto the leg side.
Ajaz Patel sees Mayank Agarwal coming down the track and hence, pushes this one wide. Agarwal reaches for it and gets it down to long on for a single.
Around the off pole, sliding on with the angle. Mayank Agarwal does well to make a bit of room and keep it out.
Pushed through quicker, on off and pushed towards short cover.
Drifted into the leg stump, Agarwal strides out to defend.
Another flatter one, on off stump and this one keeps a bit low. Axar Patel manages to keep it out on the off side.
Quicker and flatter, around off. Patel works it off the back foot towards point.
Pushed through quicker, on middle stump. Axar Patel pushes it off the back foot towards the bowler.
Slightly flatter, on middle and Patel stays solid in defense.
Tossed up, around off and turning away. Patel puts out a stride and keeps it out.
Somerville starts off with a dragged down delivery, on middle. Mayank Agarwal pulls it towards deep mid-wicket for one.
William Somerville is brought back into the attack.
Quicker one, on off and blocked out by Patel.

FOUR! Flighted ball, around off. Axar Patel plays the slog sweep this time and gets it in front of square, beating the deep mid-wicket fielder for a boundary. The fifty partnership is up between these two as well.
Tossed up, outside off. Axar Patel puts out his pads and offers no shot. The ball is turning in and hence a stifled appeal but not given.
Shorter in length, around off. Axar Patel rocks back looking to pull it down the ground but toe-end sit back to the bowler.
On off and blocked out with soft hands.
Tossed up, well outside off. Axar Patel pads it away towards backward point.
On a good-length, over off stump. Mayank Agarwal gets right behind the line of the ball to block it.
Good-length ball, around middle and leg. Agarwal looks to turn it on the leg side but gets hit on the thigh pad.
Length again, angled into middle stump. Axar Patel tucks it towards mid-wicket for a single.
Good-length ball, outside off and tapped towards point.
A length ball, on off and driven on the up towards mid off.
Well-directed short ball, around off and near the helmet. Axar Patel sways away from it.
Drifted into middle and leg, Agarwal keeps it out.
FOUR! On middle, Mayank Agarwal skips down the track, gets to the pitch of the ball and thumps it right back over the bowler's head for a boundary.
Tossed up, on off and wristed down towards long on for a single by Axar Patel.
Flatter delivery, on off and worked off the back foot towards silly mid on.
Around middle and skidding on, Patel gets it off the inner half of the bat towards square leg.
Shorter ball, on middle. Mayank Agarwal plays a half-sweep, half-pull shot towards deep square leg for one.
Fuller delivery, around off and nipping in late. Axar Patel makes another leave and it's a maiden over as well.
Length again, outside off and angled in. This one though straightens after pitching and is left alone by Patel.
Well left! Slightly pitched up, around the off pole and angling in sharply. Axar Patel makes an assured leave.
On a length, outside off and angling in. Axar Patel shoulders arms.
Back of a length, around off and played off the back foot towards point.
A good-length ball, outside off and left alone by Axar Patel.
Kyle Jamieson (10-2-35-0) comes back into the attack.
On middle, kept out.
This one goes on with the arm, it is on middle, Agarwal works it to mid-wicket.

Edge but safe! This lands on middle, straightens and also zips through. Agarwal looks to play it with a straight bat but it goes off the outside edge towards point. This pitch has started to play more tricks now.
On off, this is pushed to covers.
Nicely tossed up, gets it to dip at the end on off, Agarwal defends.
Agarwal steps down the track but Patel fires it on the pads. He tries to flick but misses to get hit on the pads.
Yet another delivery around the off pole, Patel plays it towards point.
Yet another delivery on a length and outside off, Agarwal opens the face of the bat and guides it through point for one.
Goes wide of the crease now and angles it into the off pole, Agarwal looks to defend but it goes off the inner half on the leg side.
Slightly fuller and on off, Agarwal pushes it but to mid off.
Around off, this is guided towards gully. The two batters take off initially but Henry Nicholls gets to the ball quickly and hence, stops a run.
Angled into the middle stump, Agarwal stays back and defends.
Sortish and outside off, this one turns back in a long way. Patel looks to cut but it hits the splice and rolls on the off side.
On the stumps this time, Patel works it to mid-wicket.
On off, this is pushed to the off side.
Well outside off, Patel kicks it away.
Angled into the pads, Agarwal stays back and works it through mid-wicket for one.
That lands safe! This lands on off and then turns and also bounces extra. Agarwal looks to defend, it hits the shoulder of the bat and lobs safe on the off side.
Yet another delivery on a length but the line is a harmless one, outside off, left alone.
An inswinger, this tails back in from outside off, Patel pushes it to mid on.
A tired delivery there from Southee! Full and very wide outside off, left alone.
Length and on off, Axar guides it to the fielder at gully.
Another one on a length and outside off, left alone.
Nicely played in the end! This lands outside off and then comes back in. Agarwal plays it late and guides it to point.
Just the single from the over then! Loopy ball on off, Patel goes back into his crease and keeps it out.
This lands on middle and then turns back in. Axar looks to flick but misses.
BEATEN! This is quicker and flatter outside off, goes on with the arm. Axar looks to push it away from his body but gets beaten.
Tossed up on off, Axar smothers it onto the ground.
This lands outside off and turns back in. Axar plays it really well towards mid-wicket.
Fuller and on middle, this is jammed down to long off for one.
Ajaz Patel (35-10-89-6) is back into the attack.
On the fuller side, Patel shoulders arms to this one.
Goes around the wicket, lands it on a length and on off. Patel defends it off the back foot.
Angled into the pads, Agarwal works it through square leg and gets to the other end.
Gets this one to tail back in, the line was quite far outside off though. Left alone.
Short but down the leg side. Agarwal leaves it alone. There was someone appealing, not sure who but that was well away from Agarwal.
Good length and on middle, Agarwal stands tall and defends it.

DRINKS! Ajaz Patel started the second day in fine fashion as he sent back two Indian batters in a flash. Since then though, Axar Patel has come in and given ample support to Mayank Agarwal, who is still going strong. Can the Kiwis get wickets with the new ball or will the hosts take the score over 300?
FOUR! Put away! Short and wide outside off, width on offer and it is put away. Patel cuts it through point, this one races away to the fence.
On the pads, Patel works it to mid-wicket.
On middle, Axar gets right behind the line again and keeps it out.
Quick run! On middle, this is tucked towards mid-wicket. Agarwal crosses ends.
Angled into the middle pole, Agarwal works it on the leg side. Thinks of a run but there is no run there.
Down the leg side, Agarwal looks to flick but misses.
The off cutter to the left-hander, it lands on middle and moves away a touch. Patel looks to defend, it goes more off the outer half towards the off side.
Slightly shorter in length and outside off, Patel looks to cut but underedges it on the off side.
Angled into the pads, Mayank Agarwal flicks it through square leg and takes one.
Angled into the middle poel from wide of the crease, Agarwal shows the full face of the bat and plays it back to the bowler.
Good length again and on off, Agarwal lunges and keeps it out.
Down the leg side, Agarwal looks to flick but misses.
Floats it up on off, this one turns back in. Patel leans forward and keeps it out.
Loopy ball on off, Patel lunges and keeps it out.
This is fired into the pads, Patel leaves it alone.

Does not carry! Mayank Agarwal comes down the track, he looks to go inside-out over covers which he has done brilliantly. This time though the ball turns away, goes more off the outer half towards sweeper cover for one.
Slower through the air again but outside off, spinning away further. Left alone.
A lot of turn and quick turn! Slower, it lands on off and spins away. It also zips through. Agarwal leaves it alone in the end. He was a touch surprised by the pace at which the ball went past him.
Slipping down leg! Ends the over with an in-dipper, this one though is on the pads. Patel looks to flick but misses to get hit on the pads. An appeal but turned down.
This time he looks to angle it away from the off pole, Axar gets right behind the line and blocks.
Yet another which comes back in from a length and on off, Patel is solid in defense.
Even better! Length, this starts on off and comes back in. Defended nicely. Good cricket all around.
Better! Length and gets this to shape back in from outside off, does not get it to tail back enough though to make the batter play.

FOUR! Swing straightaway but really well played! This starts on off, it tails back in late. Patel does brilliantly to get his front leg out of the way and flick it past mid-wicket. Boundary. 250 up for India.
The second new ball is now available. Will New Zealand take it straightaway? Yes, is the answer and Tim Southee (17-6-35-0) is brought back into the attack.
Quicker one, fired in on off stump. Agarwal keeps it out.
Drifted into the middle stump, Agarwal punches it out towards short cover.
Flatter one, on the pads and flicked away towards deep square leg for one.
A touch shorter, around off and turning in. Axar Patel rocks back and makes a bit off room to get it through the cover region. They come back easily for the second.
Gives it some air this time and bowls it around the off pole. Axar Patel defends it off the front foot.
On middle, pushed back towards the bowler.
Tossed up, around the leg stump and nudged towards short leg.
Slightly shorter, around off. Axar Patel goes on the back foot and nudges it towards backward point for a single.

True bounce on this occasion. Drifted into the off stump, but gripping and turning away after pitching. Patel looks to have a poke initially but seeing the turn and bounce, lets it through to the keeper.
Tossed up, fuller and on middle. Patel pushes it out towards mid on.
Outside off yet again and turning away. Patel makes an easy leave.
Nicely flighted but well outside off. Left alone by Patel.
Nicely flighted, around the leg stump. Agarwal plays it towards silly mid on.
Slightly shorter, around off. Axar Patel goes deep in his crease and punches it through cover for a run.
Outside off and played towards point.
Slightly flatter, around off and turning in sharply. Axar Patel does well to keep it out off the back foot.
Around the off pole, Patel defends it off the front foot.
On middle, Mayank Agarwal makes room and caresses it through extra cover for a single.
On off and Patel pushes it towards mid off.
On a length, around middle and leg. Mayank Agarwal hops back and works it towards deep square leg for a single.
On leg stump, pushed towards short leg by Agarwal.
Spilled well down the leg side, no shot offered.
On middle, nudged on the leg side with soft hands by Agarwal.
Just over! Looped up, around off and uppishly driven over the short cover fielder for a single.
Flatter delivery, on middle and this is squeezed out towards backward point for a run.
Nicely flighted, on middle and inviting the drive. Axar Patel works it towards short mid on.
Tossed up, around middle and kept out by Patel.
FOUR! Nicely done! On middle and turning down the leg side. Axar Patel waits for it and then just turns it past the man at leg gully and picks up a boundary.
Around middle, Patel puts a stride forward to defend.
Floated up, around off. Patel defends it out towards gully.
A touch shorter, around off. Patel cuts it off the back foot through cover-point for a single.
Angled in on off stump, put pitching outside off. Patel makes an assured leave.
Slightly slower, around middle and looking to turn it away from the left-hander. Patel keeps it out on the off side.
Fuller this time, on off and driven straight towards mid off.
Around the off pole and going straight on, well left by Axar Patel.
Around the leg stump, worked through square leg for a single.
William Somerville is on now. He needs to come good here.

In the air...safe! On a length, around off. This one holds in the surface a bit. Axar Patel looks to tuck it away off the back foot but closes the face of the bat a bit too early. The ball loops up off the leading edge and just goes over the bowler's head.
Tossed up, around off and pushed towards mid off.
Shorter one, on middle and spinning in. Patel dabs it down towards short leg.
Slightly flatter, around off and this one skids on. Axar Patel goes on the back foot to defend but gets an outside edge, past the slip cordon and they come back for the second.
Ajaz Patel gives this one a bit more air and bowls it outside off. Axar Patel strides forward and covers the line of the ball well.
On off and turning in, defended towards short leg.
Back of a length, outside off. Mayank Agarwal guides it past backward point and picks up a couple of runs.
Here comes the big in-dipper. A length ball, curving back in from outside off and Agarwal stays solid in defense.
On a length, well outside off and curving away. Mayank Agarwal shoulders arms.
FOUR! Southee strays onto the pads and Agarwal flicks it into the fine leg fence.
Slightly fuller and wide outside off, Agarwal with an easy leave.
A length ball, angled into middle and leg. Agarwal keeps it out.
No hat-trick! Tossed up, around off and turning in. Axar Patel strides out well and keeps it out.
Axar Patel walks out to bat! He will be facing the hat-trick ball.

Now then, has Ashwin been cleaned up there? He did stand there in disbelief but starts walking up. Just to be sure though, the umpires have taken it upstairs to check and replays show that the ball has crashed into the off pole.

OUT! Cleaned up! Ajaz Patel with a ripper of a delivery! Nicely flighted, around middle stump. Ravichandran Ashwin presses forward to defend but the ball then grips and turns away sharply, going past the outside edge and hitting top of off. The umpires are just making sure that the ball did hit the stumps and weren't disturbed by the keeper. The replays show that everything is fine and Ajaz Patel is on a hat-trick! Ravichandran Ashwin walks back for a golden duck. Aswhin actually did not realize he was knocked over. When the Kiwis started celebrating, he was seen indicating for a review. He thought he was given out caught behind. He later then realized that the ball had hit the stumps.
Commentary.Howout: b Ajaz Patel

Commentary.Commentary: Ravichandran Ashwin walks out to bat!

OUT! LBW! Ajaz Patel gets the breakthrough right away and picks up his fifth wicket. Quicker and flatter, just outside off. Wriddhiman Saha rocks back looking to cut it away with the spin but this one goes on with the arm and Saha gets rapped on the pads. The visitors appeal and the finger is raised. What a start from Ajaz Patel. India have been rocked early here.
Commentary.Howout: lbw b Ajaz Patel

Commentary.Commentary: On off again and turning away, edged down past first slip for a couple.
On off, Saha defends it out with soft hands.
Nicely flighted, on middle and leg. Mayank Agarwal makes room and strokes it through cover for a single.
Who will bowl from the other end? It's going to be Ajaz Patel.
Very full, around the off pole. Wriddhiman Saha eases it towards mid off and Tim Southee starts off with a maiden.
Length again, outside off and curving away. Saha makes an easy leave.
Full, on off and nudged away to silly mid on.
On off, Saha defends it off the front foot.
Lovely away shape this time. On a length, around off and swinging away. Saha keeps it out on the off side.
Southee starts off with a fullish ball, wide of off stump. Wriddhiman Saha presses forward and strokes it to cover.

We are ready for play! The umpires stride out to the middle as the New Zealand players are seen in a huddle. Out come the overnight batters for India, Wriddhiman Saha and Mayank Agarwal. Tim Southee to get proceedings underway with the ball on Day 2.

New Zealand on the other hand, will hope the others can give able support to Ajaz Patel. If not pick wickets, at least stem the run flow, the likes of Ravindra, Kyle and Somerville were quite expensive and the visitors will hope it is a different performance from them today.

What will India be looking for then? 400? Well, if they do get to that mark, it should be a really good total on a wicket which spun quite a lot on Day 1 itself. This pair holds the key, yes there is Ashwin and Jayant still left but have to believe it is not easy for a new batter to get going on this surface.

A splendid ton from Agarwal meant India head into Day 2 with their noses just ahead. Ajaz Patel though has helped kept India in check so far. The Kiwis know a couple of wickets quickly and they are right back into this one. The hosts on the other hand, are just one good partnership away from getting to an above par total. The first session of Day 2 is quite an important one. Welcome to the coverage.

Right then! That is all we have from Day 1 of the second Test match. Now India will hope they can somehow get to something around 400. New Zealand. on the other hand. will hope they can get a couple of wickets quickly and keep India in check. Do join us for the coverage of Day 2. The match starts at 9.30 am IST local (0400 GMT). Till then, take care and goodbye!

Shubman Gill is up for a quick chat. He says that he was disappointed as he got out after getting set and there was an opportunity to get more runs. Adds that early on there wasn't much spin and only the odd-ball was turning. Mentions that on surfaces like these you play with the spin and try to take the LBW out of the way when facing left-arm off-spinners. Also adds that he hasn't yet got to the hundred-run mark in his 10 Test innings so far but will look to get there soon. About Mayank's innings, he mentions that it has been a great knock and Mayank showed great character.

It all began for India with Gill and Agarwal. The two added 80 before Ajaz got three wickets in no time. Iyer and Agarwal then put up another stand but Patel struck again. That though was the last wicket as the partnership between Saha and Agarwal, who has completed his hundred, looked unbreakable.

India’s day eventually and it is all thanks to Mayank Agarwal who has played a brilliant knock. He has scored more than half the runs of his side and is the sole reason for India's position in the game.

Review time again! This time from India! Kohli has been given out LBW but he reviews immediately. Seems like there is bat. Taking some time, the umpire has no conclusive evidence if it is bat first or pad. So, the umpire has decided it is pad first, he then went onto tell the umpire to remain with his decision but  was later reminded by the on-field umpire to check Ball Tracker.

OUT! LBW! Mighty close and this is a hair-scratcher for the third umpire but the decision is made and Virat Kohli is out for a duck! On off and turning in, Kohli looks to stride out and push it out. Kohli misses and the ball raps him on the pads, plumb in front. The visitors appeal and the finger is raised but VK reviews it rightaway. The replays roll in and on UltraEdge we can see that there is bat involved. The third umpire has a good hard look at it and there is no conclusive evidence that the ball hit the bat first. Ball Tracking is then checked and three dots come up. The on field decision stays and Ajaz Patel is on seventh heaven right now!

Consecutive maidens for the visitors. Length again, just outside off and shaping away. Mayank Agarwal isn't interested in having a poke at it.
Southee attacks the pads this time as Agarwal eases it towards mid on.
A length ball, angled in at off stump but moves away after pitching. Agarwal makes yet another leave.
Lovely away shape yet again. In the channel, just outside off and Agarwal makes a watchful leave.
Southee pitches it up, around off and this one shapes away nicely. Agarwal shoulders arms.
A length ball, well outside off but swinging away as well. Mayank Agarwal leaves it alone.
Tossed up, on middle. Cheteshwar Pujara works it towards mid-wicket where the fielder makes a half-stop. Pujara wants the single but won't get it. End of a wicket-maiden over from Ajaz Patel.
On middle again and defended off the front foot by Pujara.
On middle, Pujara blocks.
Cheteshwar Pujara comes in at number 3.

OUT! TAKEN! They do get it this time as Taylor makes no mistake. Blundell will be a relieved man. A well-deserved wicket for Ajaz Patel. He has been brilliant. He once again gives it air, lands it on off and gets it to turn away. Gill pushes at it, he does so ahead of his body. It goes off the outside edge and Taylor at first slip takes it. Gill does not make most of the start he got. Can New Zealand now make most of this?
Commentary.Howout: c Ross Taylor b Ajaz Patel

Commentary.Commentary: Stumping chance goes abegging! Beautiful bowling. Floats it up, lands it outside off, tempts the batter. Gill skips down the track, he does not quite get to the pitch of the ball but looks to drive, it lands, turns, goes past the outside edge and there is also extra bounce. Blundell looks to collect the ball but it goes off the outer part towards the off side. Gill makes it back in. This chance needed to be taken. New Zealand need a wicket.
On off, defended.
On middle, eased down to long on for one.
Shorter one, around off, punched off the back foot towards cover.
FOUR! On middle, Shubman Gill gets down on one knee and sweeps it into the mid-wicket fence.
Nicely tossed up, slower in pace and on middle. Gill looks to clip it on the leg side but the ball goes off the inside edge past short leg.
FOUR! Short and wide, thoroughly punished by Shubman Gill. Gill rocks back and cuts it away into the cover-point fence.
Around middle and leg, dabbed down on the leg side.
Beaten! Ajaz Patel pitches it further up, around the off pole. The ball grips and turns away sharply. Patel looks to drive but gets beaten on the outside edge.
Around off, Agarwal strides out to defend.
Nicely tossed up, on middle and drifting in. Agarwal defends it out.
Around off and kept out on the off side.
Slowed up, on off and allowing the ball to turn. Agarwal cuts it towards backward point.
Flatter one, around middle and leg. Agarwal works it off the back foot towards mid-wicket.

DRINKS! India are going along really well here! They are in a strong position courtesy their openers. The two are playing really aggressively and are laying a good foundation for a big score. New Zealand on the other hand, need wickets or they will be batted out of the ga.e WIll the break work for them?
On leg stump and flicked towards short fine leg for an easy single.
Nicely flighted, around middle. Agarwal lunges out to defend.
On a length, around leg stump and going further down. Agarwal looks to flick but misses and the ball goes off the keeper's mitts towards short fine leg. Gill wants the single but is sent back.
Slightly shorter, around middle and leg. Gill hops back and works it towards square leg for a single.
Down the leg side, padded away towards square leg.
TWO LEG BYES! William Somerville sees Gill advancing and drifts down the leg side. Gill pads it away towards fine leg and picks up a couple of leg byes.
Very full again, on middle. Mayank Agarwal drives it towards mid on.
Full and around middle and leg, pushed back towards the bowler.
Pushed through, around off and well kept out by Agarwal.
A touch short and wide, played with the spin towards cover-point.
On a length, around leg stump. Agarwal goes on the back foot to defend but gets rapped on the pads.
TWO LEG BYES! Quicker one, down the leg side. Mayank Agarwal looks to flick it away but the ball goes off the pads towards fine leg and they get a couple of leg byes as well.
On a length, around middle and kept out on the leg side.
Gill looks to use his feet but Somerville angles it at his pads and Gill can't get it away.
On the pads, Agarwal tickles it fine and picks up a single.
Well that one certainly spun a long way. On leg stump, spinning way down the leg side. Good take from the keeper.
Around middle and leg, Agarwal plays it with soft hands towards the leg side.
On middle, defended towards short mid on.
Tossed up, on off and kept out by Gill.
Full and on leg stump, Gill jams it out back to the bowler.
Drifting in on middle and leg, Gill defends it off the front foot.
On the pads, pushed out towards short mid-wicket.
Slowed up, on a length and around off. Agarwal waits for it and works it past point for a single.
Beaten! On a nagging length, outside off. Agarwal goes on the back foot to cut it away but gets beaten by the turn and bounce.
SIX! A sweet, sweet strike from Shubman Gill. Tossed up, on middle. Gill dances down the track and slogs it with the spin, well over the mid-wicket fence for a biggie.
Nicely flighted, around middle and leg and turning in. Gill steps out of his crease but manages to get his pads in the way.
Floated up, on the pads and worked past short leg for a single by Agarwal.
Slightly shorter, on middle. Defended off the back foot to short leg.
Flighted ball, on off. Agarwal defends it back to the bowler.
On middle and leg, nudged with soft hands towards short mid-wicket.
On off, it is pushed to covers.
Flatter and on the stumps, blocked.
Lovely stuff! Slower, lands it on off, bringing the batter forward. Gilll lunges and tries to defend, the ball lands and spins away. Beaten.
Slower through the air and on off, defended.
Now the one that comes back in with the arm. Blocked.
Flatter and on middle, this lands and turns away. Gill defends it off the back foot.
A single now as this is eased down to long on for one.
Fuller and on middle, this is eased down to long on for one.
Down the leg side, Agarwal shoulders arms to this one.
On middle, Agarwal works it to mid-wicket.

FOUR! Just wide! That is more off the inner half! Agarwal comes down the track, he looks to go over mid on but the ball turns back in, it goes more off the inner half wide of the mid-wicket fielder and into the fence.
Fifty up for India! A really good start for them. On middle, Gill works it through mid-wicket for one.
On middle, blocked.
On off, defended nicely this time. This one goes on with the arm. It is usually the ones that do not turn which get the batter out.

That is a beauty! Ajaz just slows it up a little, he lands it on middle, slightly shorter, it pitches and turns square. Agarwal is beaten all ends up as he tries to block. This is just the first session and that was big turn.
On off, Agarwal plays it late and to point.
Fires it on middle, Agarwal gets right behind the line and defends.
On off, this is pushed down to long off for one.
On off, Agarwal pushes it towards cover. There could have been a single but Agarwal sends him back.
On middle, Agarwal works it to short leg.
Just over! Agarwal comes down the track, he gets a full toss, he lifts it over the leaping fielder at mid-wicket. Two taken.
Fuller and on off, this is pushed to mid off.
On off, defended.
Gill comes down the track and makes it into a low full toss, it is hit towards mid off for one.
Spin from both ends now as William Somerville is brought into the attack.
A testing over from Patel. A maiden! On middle, Agarwal plays it to covers.
Very full and on middle, this is jammed out to mid off.
Slightly fuller and on off, Agarwal pushes it to mid off.
Another one which angles into middle and then straightens. Agarwal looks to block, it goes off the outer half to point.

The umpires have gone upstairs for a Stumping appeal. They will check the edge as well. UltraEdge shows that there's no bat involved and the replay confirms that the back leg was firmly rooted inside the crease. NOT OUT!

NOT OUT! Mayank Agarwal is well in and no spike on Ultra Edge too! This is angled into the off pole. It lands and then spins away sharply. Agarwal lunges to block but is beaten. The keeper whips the bails off and appeals. It is referred but Agarwal is well and truly safe.
Fuller and on middle, this is pushed to mid on.
Outside off, Gill shoulders arms to this one.
Another one on off, Gill stands tall and pushes it to covers.
Gets this one to shape away! A little though and the line is outside off. Left alone.
Angled into the middle pole, Gill pushes it to mid on.
Goes wide of the crease and angles it into the off pole, defended.
On off, Gill plays it to point.
Well fielded! Shorter and outside off, Agarwal cuts but the fielder at point dives to his right and stops it.
Darts it on middle, blocked.

SIX! That is a lovely shot! Goes all the way. First of the game. Mayank Agarwal dances down the track and this time gets to the pitch of it. He lofts it over the bowler's head and over long off for a biggie.
Uppish but well wide! Angled into the pads, Agarwal looks to defend, it goes off the inner half but wide of short leg.
On middle, Agarwal defends it.
Patel skips down the track but ends up yorking himself. It is jammed out to covers.
Outside off, Gill guides it to point.
Another one on the stumps, defended.
Aronnd off, Gill plays it out on the off side.
On off and on a length, defended.
On off, Gill stands tall and defends.

EDGY FOUR! Gill won't mind though. That went all along the ground. Length and on off, this lands and moves away. Gill looks to defend, it goes off the outside edge, past first slip and into the third man fence.
Kyle Jamieson (3-0-20-0) comes back into the attack.
Agarwal skips down the track, Ajaz bowls a full toss, Agarwal misses out as he hits it straight to the mid off fielder.
Angled into the leg pole, Agarwal looks to defend but gets an inside edge onto the pads.
On off, Gill pushes it to mid off for a quick run.
Flatter and on middle, Gill defends.
FOUR! Up and over! Lovely stroke! Steps out and gets to the pitch of the ball. He lofts it over covers, goes inside-out and bags a boundary.
On middle, defended.

DRINKS! India have got off to a decent start with the bat and will be happy to see off the new ball without losing a wicket. As for New Zealand, the ball really swung in the first over and after that we have seen hints of swing and nothing more. Can New Zealand pick up the first wicket or will the Indian openers keep on gathering runs?
And again, takes a few steps ahead and then blocks this length ball onto the ground.
Attacks the stumps, this time, defended.

A good leave in the end! Gill skips down the track and also makes room. Southee goes wide of the crease and angles it into the off pole. Gill shoulders arms to it, the ball does come in with the angle but goes just past the off pole.
Yet another one on off, Gill lunges and keeps it out.
Probably realises the bumper is not the delivery you want to bowl on this surface. He goes back to length and on off, Gill plays it late and towards point.
A bumper, comes slow off the surface. Gill just watches it go to the keeper. Good bounce but it was more of a tennis-ball like bounce.
Tossed up, on off and worked towards short cover. Maiden over from Ajaz Patel.
On a length, around middle and turning away a bit. Mayank Agarwal defends it off the back foot.
Very full again, on off and punched away to short cover.
Slightly tossed up, full and around off. Agarwal strokes it towards cover-point.
Fired in at off stump, Agarwal defends it under his eyeline.
On middle and this is pushed back to the bowler.
Good-length ball, around middle. Gill keeps it out towards mid on.
On a nagging length, just around off. Agarwal looks to defend but the ball goes off the inside edge towards short mid on. The batters do scamper through for a quick single.
On middle and leg, tucked away to deep mid-wicket for a single.
Bowled from wide of the crease this time by Southee. Fullish ball, well outside off, Gill drives it off the inner half of the bat towards the cover region.
In that channel outside off and shaping away. Gill leaves it alone.
Full and on off, jammed out towards cover-point for a single by Agarwal.

In the air...safe! Quicker one, on middle and leg and this one grips and turns as well. Mayank Agarwal looks to sweep yet again but is caught on the crease as his shot goes up in the air and lands safely around the square leg region. Single taken.
Sharp turn! On middle, Mayank Agarwal looks to sweep but the ball spins away sharply and the ball comes off the toe-end of the bat and goes on the off side.
On middle, Mayank Agarwal strides out to defend.
Patel pulls back his length a bit and bowls it on off stump. The ball turns away a bit after pitching and Agarwal cuts it towards point.
On off and kept out on the off side.
Patel starts off with a low full toss, on the pads. Agarwal nudges it towards short mid-wicket.
Change! Ajaz Patel is on! Time for some spin.

Beaten all ends up! Southee bowls a pearler of an inswinger to end the over, Pitched up, outside off and Gill looks to drive again but this time the ball nips back and goes through the huge gap between bat and pad. End of a maiden from Southee.
Good shot for no run. Full and around off, driven nicely but straight to mid off.
Gill comes down the track and taps the length ball towards cover-point.
Fullish ball, outside off. Gill punches the cover drive straight to the cover fielder.
Nicely bowled! Pitched up, in that channel around off and shaping away. Gill with a watchful leave.
A length ball, well outside off and swinging further away. No shot offered from Shubman Gill.
A bouncer now, outside the off stump. Mayank Agarwal ducks under it.
Length again, on off and angled in. Agarwal gets right behind the line of the ball to block it.
Full and on off, Agarwal edges it down towards gully.
A length ball, over middle. Agarwal defends it off the back foot.
FOUR! Edgy! Length again, just around the off pole. Mayank Agarwal gets squared up but goes at it with soft hands. The outside edge goes past the slip cordon and into the third man fence.
A length ball, on middle and tailing into the pads. Agarwal manages to fend it away on the leg side.
Good-length ball, around middle. Gill dabs it down towards short mid-wicket.
Fullish ball, around off and Agarwal times the cover drive well. The fielder at extra cover does well to dive to his left and make a half-stop. Single taken.
A length ball, around off and this one nips back in off the surface. Mayank Agarwal looks to defend it off the front foot but gets an inside edge onto the pads.
Fuller delivery, outside off and swinging away. Agarwal shoulders arms.
Nice away movement but the ball is bowled well outside off. Mayank Agarwal with an easy leave.
Pitched up, outside off. Agarwal looks to drive but lets it through in the end.
Slightly pitched up, on off. Gill stays solid in defense.
Uppish but in the gap! On middle and tailing back in, Mayank Agarwal clips it through mid-wicket and they come back for the third with ease.
Good-length ball, outside off and shaping away. Agarwal shoulders arms.
Hint of swing on this occasion. Full, around middle and shaping away. Agarwal defends it back to the bowler.
A length ball, well outside off. Mayank Agarwal isn't interested in having a poke at that one.
Good running! Back of a length, angled at the body. Gill dabs it down towards short mid-wicket and sets off for a quick single.
Good-length ball, on off. Mayank Agarwal nudges it towards the cover region.
Length again, around the off pole. Agarwal keeps it out with soft hands on the off side.
A length ball, outside off. Agarwal defends it towards cover.
Fuller delivery, targeting the toes of the batter. Agarwal flicks it towards short mid-wicket.
On top of off, Agarwal defends it off the front foot.
FOUR! Mayank Agarwal gets off the mark with a shot almost identical to Gill's first shot. On middle and leg, nicely clipped through mid-wicket and into the fence.
FOUR! Uppish but safe! On the pads yet again from Jamieson and Gill flicks this one in front of square and picks up a boundary.
Short and wide, Gill hangs back and taps it towards cover-point. No timing on that one.
Angled in on middle and leg, Gill keeps it out on the leg side.
A length ball, close to the off stump. Gill lets it through to the keeper.
FOUR! Two in a row! Full and wide, shaping away nicely. Shubman Gill leans into the drive and creams it through cover for another boundary.
FOUR! Shubman Gill gets the innings started in fine style. Kyle Jamieson starts off with a half-volley on the pads. Gill plays the drive through mid-wicket and picks up a boundary.
Who will bowl from the other end then? Will the Kiwis go for a spinner or will it be Kyle Jamieson? Kyle Jamieson it is.
Here comes the inswinger. On a length, around off and nipping in sharply. Mayank Agarwal strides out to defend but gets an inside edge onto the pads. Tim Southee starts off with a maiden.

Tim Southee seems confident but no one else appeals. Southee pitches it up, on off stump and there's the away movement yet again. Agarwal squeezes it out towards gully. Southee probably thought it was pad first. He put in a loud, loud appeal. It was right off the centre.
Right on the money this time from Southee. On middle and nipping away, Agarwal keeps it out on the off side.
Good away shape yet again but a bit too outside off. Another easy leave for Mayank Agarwal.
A length ball, outside off and shaping away a bit. Mayank Agarwal shoulders arms.
Swing straightaway for Tim Southee. Fullish ball, around the off pole. The ball shapes away after pitching and Mayank Agarwal makes an assured leave.

We are finally ready for play! The umpires are out in the middle as Tom Latham is seen leading his team onto the ground. Mayank Agarwal and Shubman Gill are the openers for India. Tim Southee has the new ball in hand.

New Zealand captain, Tom Latham says they wanted to bat too but the wicket has been under cover so if there is anything in it, it would be early on. States the way they got the ball to swing in Kanpur was really good and he hopes they can get some here. Mentions the last result was a morale booster and they will try and adapt quickly here too.

The Indian skipper, Virat Kohli says it looks like a good wicket, nice and hard and today maybe the best day to bat on. Informs there are a few changes, a few niggle based, Rahane, Ishant and Jadeja are out and Yadav, himself and Siraj come in. States they need to do the basics right, New Zealand did really well in the last game, they gave it their all but the Kiwis were really good.

New Zealand (Playing XI) - Tom Latham (C), Will Young, Daryl Mitchell (In for Kane Williamson), Ross Taylor, Henry Nicholls, Tom Blundell (WK), Rachin Ravindra, Tim Southee, Ajaz Patel, Kyle Jamieson, William Somerville.

India (Playing XI) - Mayank Agarwal, Shubman Gill, Cheteshwar Pujara, Virat Kohli (C) (In for Ajinkya Rahane), Shreyas Iyer, Wriddhiman Saha (WK), Ravichandran Ashwin, Jayant Yadav (In for Ravindra Jadeja), Axar Patel, Umesh Yadav, Mohammed Siraj (In for Ishant Sharma).
TOSS - Up goes the flip of the coin and Tom Latham calls it. The coin lands in favor of Virat Kohli and he elects to BAT first.

UPDATE 1035 local time (0505 GMT) - Right then, we have good news from the middle. The toss will now take place at 1130 local time (0600 GMT) and play is expected to begin at 1200 local time (0630 GMT). Early Lunch will be taken and the first session will go on from 1200 local time (0630 GMT) till 1440 (0910 GMT). There will be a Tea interval of 20 minutes and the final session will go on from 1500 local time (0930 GMT) till 1730 (1200 GMT).

It is now confirmed that Kane Williamson is ruled out of this Test due to a shoulder injury and Tom Latham will captain the New Zealand side. This also means that neither of the captains from the first Test even feature in the second one. We are pretty sure that this hardly ever happens.

The wait here continues but if you’re eager to follow some live-action, you can switch tabs and catch all the action from the Lanka game. It is Day 5 there and all three results are possible. A Lanka win or a draw looks a lot more likely than a Windies win but we have seen the West Indian teams do unbelievable things on the last day of Tests before. Also, it is the last day of Mickey Arthur as Lankan coach. Will his side give him the perfect farewell?

UPDATE 0935 local time (0405 GMT) - The umpires are in the middle and they have decided that a couple of areas in the infield are still pretty wet and play cannot start unless these areas are considered safe for the fielding side. They also decide that there will be another inspection at 1030 local time (0500 GMT). Stay tuned for further updates.

Some team news coming from the Indian camp. Ajinkya Rahane, Ishant Sharma and Ravindra Jadeja have been ruled out of this Test match due to injury concerns. This is a body blow for the hosts. Who will replace them? Virat Kohli will definitely come in for Rahane, probably Siraj for Ishant, but who will replace Jadeja? We'll have to wait and watch.

We have no official word as of now but it seems like Kane Williamson might not be playing this Test. He might be struggling with the elbow injury he already had. We write this as we see he’s not out there, holding his bat and doing some knocking. If he doesn’t feature, it will be Latham who will lead.

PITCH REPORT - Ajit Agarkar and Deep Dasgupta are pitchside. Ajit says that the pitch might hold a bit more as it's been under cover and there are a few cracks already. There will be spin on offer and it will be quick spin here. DDG adds that there might also be something early on for the seamers and three out of the last four wins here have come for sides batting second but it's tricky this time around and it might be a good toss to lose.

Anil Chaudhary, the umpire for the match says they aren’t starting on time, the run up area is an issue and they will assess it at 9:30 am and he hopes things get fine with the sunshine. Nitin Menon, the other umpire says the main concern is the in-field and they will assess the conditions at 9:30 am and informs the wicket is fine.
The toss which was scheduled for 9 am local (3:30 am GMT) has been delayed due to wet outfield. There will be an official inspection at 9:30 am local (4 am GMT).

The Kiwis, will they go with just the two pacers again or will Neil Wagner get the nod in place of Somerville? The offie wasn’t that effective with the ball but his innings with the bat in his sides’ second essay was pretty crucial. Also, teams usually do not tinker with their winning XI but you just never know considering the problems the visitors’ pacers caused in the last game. All of the above questions too will be answered shortly, stay tuned for the toss in a bit.

Now, let’s talk a little about the teams. India first - there’s just the one question looming around everyone’s head right now and that is who will make way for Virat Kohli? Will it be Pujara, will Iyer, who had a magical debut sit out or will Agarwal get the axe? If Agarwal does get dropped, who will open? Too many questions and pretty sure you’ll are as eager to know as we are and we will find out shortly.

First things first, let us talk about the weather. Yes, you read it right, the weather! You might be wondering what could be wrong with the weather in December in India, well, it has been raining in Mumbai for the last two days but the good news is, there are no signs of rain today and the conditions seem excellent for cricket.

Excellent display of grit, determination and character from the Kiwi batters saw them salvage a draw in the first Test. Now, it is time for the second and final game of the series. A win for either side will see them seal the series. The Kiwis, after that morale boosting result will be confident heading into this one. The Indians on the other hand, will want nothing less than a win. Mumbai is the venue and we can expect another cracker of a game. Welcome to the coverage.
... MATCH DAY ...
We are back! New Zealand players are there in the middle. The Indian openers Mayank Agarwal and Cheteshwar Pujara make their way out to the middle as well. Tim Southee to start for New Zealand.
... Innings Break ...

The Kiwis now will have to come out to bowl again as India have not enforced the follow-on. They will start with a lead of 263. They would now look to bat New Zealand completely out of the game. The Kiwis will hope they can bowl India out quickly.

New Zealand just surrendered. It was a sorry performance by them with the bat. None of their batters managed to cross the 2-run mark and also, just the two managed to score in double digits. Speaks volumes about how poor they were.

End of a magical bowling performance from India! They have bowled out for 62 which is Kiwis' lowest total against India. It was a combined bowling effort. Siraj was the one started it off with three early on and then the spinners did their job. Ashwin then weaved his magic with a four-fer and Axar and Jayant also played their part.

OUT! CAUGHT! It's all over! New Zealand have been bundled out for 62. Their lowest ever total against India! Axar Patel bowls this slower in the air on off. Kyle Jamieson looks to hit it away but the ball catches the outside edge of his blade and goes to Wriddhiman Saha behind the stumps. The ball hits him and loops in the air towards the off side. Shreyas Iyer at silly point dives to his left and takes a fantastic catch. The umpire gives that out but Kyle Jamieson reviews. The replays roll in and UltraEdge shows a spike as the ball passes his blade and Kyle Jamieson has to walk back.
Commentary.Howout: c Shreyas Iyer b Axar Patel

Commentary.Commentary: Kyle Jamieson has taken the review for the catch and it seems like its in desperation. UltraEdge confirms that there's a faint knick and the catch is clean as well. OUT!
Quicker but spraying down the leg side. Ajaz Patel looks to get a bat on that one but the ball is way down the leg side.
Ajaz Patel is the last man in for New Zealand.

OUT! The resistance of William Somerville comes to an end! It was a gritty 26 ball duck for William Somerville but he has to depart now. Ravichandran Ashwin tosses it up, on off and Somerville looks to clear mid on. He though ends up chipping it straight towards Mohammed Siraj at mid on and the catch is taken. Ashwin gets his fourth now and just one wicket remains for the visitors.
Commentary.Howout: c Mohammed Siraj b Ravichandran Ashwin

Commentary.Commentary: William Somerville dances down the track and manages to keep it down towards short leg.
Tossed up, on middle and this is flicked away through mid-wicket for a single.
Flatter one, on off and spinning in. Kyle Jamieson rocks back and keeps it down on the leg side.
Turning too much. On middle and leg, Kyle Jamieson looks to nudge it on the on side but misses and gets rapped on the pads.
Flatter and quicker outside off. William Somerville looks to push at it but the ball misses the outside edge of his blade.
Tossed up on middle. William Somerville blocks it out to short leg.
Ohh.. extra bounce there! Slower in the air on middle. The ball bounces a little as Kyle Jamieson looks to defend it. He gets an inside edge onto his pads towards mid on for a single.
Quicker and flatter on middle. Kyle Jamieson gets forward and defends it again solidly.
Fuller and flatter again on middle. Kyle Jamieson pushes it to mid on.
Axar Patel darts this quicker on off and middle. Kyle Jamieson blocks this off the back foot.
Nicely tossed up on middle again, William Somerville blocks it out.
Tossed up on middle. Turned away to mid-wicket.
Flatter and quicker outside off this time. William Somerville looks to cut but misses.
Nicely tossed up on middle again. William Somerville defends this off the inner half of his blade to short leg.
Slower in the air on middle. William Somerville defends this off the front foot.
Shorter length around off. Punched towards the cover region.
Flatter and angling into middle and leg. Kyle Jamieson presses forward to defend it.
On off and fuller. Defended off the front foot towards silly point.
Another quicker delivery on off. Kyle Jamieson defends it with straight bat off the front foot.
Flatter on off again. Kyle Jamieson gets his pads across and leaves it alone.
Flatter and shorter on off. Kyle Jamieson punches it to covers.
Flatter delivery on off. Kyle Jamieson blocks it off the back foot.
Tosses it up on off, it is pushed to mid off.
Comes down the track and works it to mid on.
NO BALL! Once again a short leg fielder is hit but he seems okay now! A full toss on middle, William Somerville pulls it hard but it hits Iyer at short leg. He seems fine though.
Shorter and on off, this is pushed to covers.
On middle, defended.

NOT OUT! Great take from Wriddhiman Saha but William Somerville survives! On middle and leg, spins way down the leg side. William Somerville charges down the track but gets beaten in flight. He though quickly scampers back into the crease. Saha dives to his left and in one smooth motion, pouches the ball and whips off the bails. The replays show that the bat was grounded.
Is that a stumping? The umpires have gone upstairs for a stumping shout. UltraEdge confirms that there is no bat involved and the replay shows that the bat was well rooted inside the crease. NOT OUT!
Shorter length outside off. William Somerville looks to cut but misses.
Tossed up on off. Kyle Jamieson gets forward and looks to defend.The ball kisses the outside edge of his blade and goes towards short third man.
Shorter length, on off. Punched off the back foot towards the off side.
Slightly slower in air on off. Kyle Jamieson gets forward and defends it.
Flatter and quicker on off. Defended off the front foot.

FOUR! Short ball and punished! Shorter length outside off. Kyle Jamieson goes deep in his crease and punches it through covers for a boundary. Good effort by Mohammed Siraj there but the ball crosses the ropes.
Flatter on off. Kyle Jamieson gets forward and defends it to the off side.
Flighted ball, on off and spinning it yet again. William Somerville gets forward and pads it straight to short leg who pouches it.
On middle and leg, worked on the leg side.
On off, Somerville presses forward and pushes it out on the off side.
William Somerville comes down the track but gets completely beaten in flight. This is on off and turns in, Somerville looks to work it on the on side but the ball goes off the pads onto the off side.
Flighted ball, on middle and Somerville keeps it out.
Uppish but safe! Tossed up, on off. Kyle Jamieson chips it towards mid off for a single.
Flatter one, on off and kept out on the off side.
Tossed up, on middle and kept out by William Somerville.
On middle and leg, pushed towards mid on.
On off, blocked.
Angled into the pads, this is worked through mid-wicket for one.
On off, blocked.

OUT! CAUGHT! Ravichandran Ashwin is in a hurry to clean up the New Zealand tail now. Ashwin loops it up, around the off pole and allows the pitch to do the rest. The ball spins in as Tim Southee looks to press forward and poke at it. The ball goes off the inside edge, onto the pads and loops up towards short leg. The substitute fielder, Suryakumar Yadav dives forward and takes a good catch. William Somerville walks in at number 10 for New Zealand.
Commentary.Howout: c sub Suryakumar Yadav b Ravichandran Ashwin

Commentary.Commentary: On middle and flicked away onto the leg side.
Tim Southee walks out to bat now.

OUT! TAKEN! Another good bit of catching and down goes the seventh wicket for New Zealand! Ravichandran Ashwin tosses it up again, on off stump. The ball turns in and Tom Blundell doesn't really come forward as he looks to push it out. Blundell gets an inside edge, back onto the pads and towards backward short leg. Cheteshwar Pujara takes a good low catch to his right and Tom Blundell's short resistance comes to an end.
Commentary.Howout: c Cheteshwar Pujara b Ravichandran Ashwin

Commentary.Commentary: Slightly flatter, on off and edged down towards backward point for one.
Flighted ball, on off and turning in. Kyle Jamieson looks to block but gets an inside edge onto the pads.
Floated up, on leg stump and nudged out on the on side.
Slowed up, on a length and outside off. Tom Blundell goes on the back foot to dab it down towards square leg.
Quicker one, on middle. This is eased down to mid on for a quick single.
Around middle and nudged onto the leg side.
FOUR! Precious runs for New Zealand these. Tossed up, on middle and leg. Kyle Jamieson plays it with the spin and clips it through wide mid on for a boundary.
A touch short yet again, on the pads. Tom Blundell flicks it off the back foot onto the leg side for a single.
FOUR! Poor delivery, dragged down, on leg stump. Tom Blundell has all the time in the world to rock back and pulls it into the square leg fence.

Dropped! It wouldn't have counted anyway as a no ball is called for overstepping. Slightly shorter, on leg stump. Kyle Jamieson hits it aerially towards short mid on, where Shubman Gill drops it and the batters scamper through for a run as well.
On the stumps and well kept out by Tom Blundell.
Uppish but safe! Flighted delivery, on middle and leg, Blundell flicks it just past short leg.
Quicker and very full, on off. Kyle Jamieson squeezes it out on the off side for a single.
Was there any bat on it? No, there wasn't but a good take at leg slip nonetheless. On middle and turning down leg, Kyle Jamieson looks to flick but the ball goes off the pads towards leg slip.
Beaten! Nicely tossed up, around the off pole, inviting the drive. Kyle Jamieson goes for it but gets undone by the flight and spin as the ball goes between bat and pad.
Quicker one, at 91 kph, on off stump. Kyle Jamieson manages to keep it out.
Who will bowl from the other end? It's going to be Ravichandran Ashwin.
On a length, on the pads. Kyle Jamieson works it past short leg and picks up a single.
Spilled down the leg side, left alone.
We are back for the final session! Tom Blundell and the new man, Kyle Jamieson are out in the middle. Jayant Yadav has the ball in hand and will finish his incomplete over.
... Day 2, Session 3 ...

New Zealand, not sure what can save them at the moment, they are on the mat. They just have the bowling all-rounders to come. They will probably be targeting to somehow avoid the follow-on but that too seems far away. We may see them play a few shots after the break as more than survival, runs is what they need. Do join us to see if the Kiwis can fight back.

Ajaz Patel, the man of the hour, is up for a quick chat. He says that it is a special occasion for him and for his family as well but they can't be here today due to covid restrictions. Adds that one never believes that they can get all ten wickets because it's all just so surreal. He knows that the first man to take 10 wickets in an innings, Jim Laker also played for Yorkshire like himself and he is happy about it. Mentions that right now they are under a bit of pressure but believes that the batters can put on a few more runs and get them back into the match.

It was Siraj who started things off as he got three in no time. Then the spinners played their role. Axar struck first and then it was Ashwin and Yadav. Just the 4 wickets away and New Zealand are still 88 away from avoiding the follow-on, India could well have a chance of enforcing it after the break.

India just could not have asked for a better session! If there is anything such as a perfect session then this is it! Yes, the initial stages may have belonged Ajaz Patel but the Indian bowlers have put in an outstanding collective effort.

OUT! TAKEN! Jayant Yadav strikes in his first over as well as the umpires signal for the Tea break. Just like the first delivery Yadav bowled, this one is drifted in, on middle stump. The ball yet again grips and turns away sharply. There is extra bounce on offer as well. Rachin Ravindra presses forward to defend but this time the outside edge is found. Virat Kohli, at first slip takes a sharp catch to his right and Jayant Yadav is elated.
Commentary.Howout: c Virat Kohli b Jayant Yadav

Commentary.Commentary: Nicely flighted, around off and defended off the front foot.
On off, pushed out on the off side.
What a beauty! Jayant Yadav tosses it up, the ball drifts in a bit, on off and the ball just grips nicely. The ball then turns sharply and just goes past the outside edge.
Tossed up, on middle and leg. Blundell dabs it down towards square leg.
On the pads, kept out on the leg side.

Opportunity missed! Quicker one, on middle and played towards short mid-wicket. A slight mix-up between the batters as they decide to go for the quick run. Shreyas Iyer does well to get to it in a flash but the throws is just too high.
On the pads, nudged through backward square leg for a couple.
This one turned square! Tossed up, around off and the ball just spins a mile away from the batter.
Looped up, around the leg stump. Rachin Ravindra defends it right under his eyeline.
Slowed up, on off and Tom Blundell stays solid in defense.
Around off and dabbed down towards backward point with soft hands for a single by Rachin Ravindra.
Tossed up, on middle and leg, spinning into the left-hander. Rachin Ravindra strides out to defend but misses and gets rapped on the pads. Just the bowler appeals, probably spinning down leg.
Flatter one, around middle. Tom Blundell nudges it off the back foot towards mid-wicket for a single.
On off and kept out towards silly point.
A short delivery, on middle and leg. Tom Blundell rocks back and works it in front of square on the leg side for a couple.
Nicely flighted, on middle and kept out. Ravichandran Ashwin starts off with a wicket-maiden.
Drifting into middle and leg, Rachin Ravindra blocks it out with soft hands.
On middle, flicked away by Ravindra.
A touch flatter, around off and tapped onto the off side.
On off and watchfully kept out by Ravindra.

OUT! BOWLED! Ravichandran Ashwin comes in and knocks Henry Nicholls over off the very first delivery! Ashwin starts from around the wicket and pushes it through a bit quicker and on the off stump. Henry Nicholls looks to stride and defend with the spin but this one just goes on with the arm. Nicholls completely misses it and the ball goes through the gap between bat and pad, crashing into off stump. New Zealand in dire straits now. Rachin Ravindra comes in at number 7.
Commentary.Howout: b Ravichandran Ashwin

Commentary.Commentary: Quick run! On middle, this is worked towards mid-wicket. A single taken.

Shubman Gill gets a nasty blow at short leg and is some in some pain. The physio is coming out to have a look. Hope he is fine. The ball missed the elbow guard and hit him from close range, those blows do sting a lot. Everything seems fine now and we are ready to continue.
OUCH! That must have hurt! Big time! Nicholls comes down the track and then nails the sweep. It hits Gill at short leg flush near the elbow.

NOT OUT! Nicholls is well in! Good running! On off, Nicholls looks to sweep but due to the extra bounce, it goes off the top edge, it lands safe in the fine leg region. The batters go for the second. The throw is to the keeper who whips the bails off. It is referred and replays show that the batsman is well in.

Is that a Run-Out? The throws come in at the keeper's end as Wriddhiman Saha whips off the bails and the umpires go upstairs to have a look. The replays roll in and Henry Nicholls was well in. Not Out!
On off, blocked.
Really good keeping! This lands on middle and turns back in sharply. Nicholls looks to flick but misses. It hits the pad and Saha takes it well down the leg side.
On off, defended after taking a couple of steps down the track.

After a long discussion, India do not review and rightly so! The impact seemed outside off and it looked like there was no edge. Length outside off, this one jags back in. Blundell gets outside the line of off and looks to push at it but misses. It seems to have taken the pad and gone to the keeper. An appeal but turned down.
Angled into the pads, Nicholls looks to flick but misses. It hits the pad and rolls on the leg side. A leg bye taken.
Yet another length delivery outside off, Nicholls does not play at it.
Yet another length ball on off, Henry comes forward and defends it.
Outside off, another length ball, left alone.
Fullish and on off, this is driven but to covers.
Lands well short! On off, this one holds its line. Blundell looks to defend but it goes off the outside edge but lands well short of the second slip fielder.
On off, this is pushed to covers.
Floats it up on off, this is pushed to mid off.
On off, Blundell is solid in defense.
Slower through the air and on middle, Tom leans forward and keeps it out.
On middle, Blundell leans forward and blocks.
A harmless nut to end! Outside off, left alone.
Fuller and on off, Nicholls pushes it to mid off.
Angled into the pads, Nicholls looks to flick but misses to get hit on the pads.
On off, this is pushed to mid on.
Solid stuff! Length and on off, Henry stands tall and plays it back to the bowler.
A good-length ball, outside off and angling across. Left alone by Henry Nicholls.
Umesh Yadav (3-0-7-0) comes back into the attack.
On off, slightly shorter, this is pushed to covers.
Attacks the stumps yet again, blocked.
Quicker and outside off, left alone.
Another one on the stumps, kept out.
Flatter and on off, Tom guides it to point.

DRINKS! After that beautiful burst from Ajaz Patel to clean up the Indian tail, the Indian bowlers have come out all guns blazing. Mohammed Siraj, in particular, has bowled extremely well and sent back three of the top order batters. Just at the stroke of this break, Axar Patel has picked up India's fourth wicket and the hosts are truly in command here. Also, Tom Blundell walks out to bat at number 6.

For the second time in the last few overs, Daryl Mitchell takes the review for an LBW decision. UltraEdge confirms that there's no inside edge and Ball Tracker shows up three reds. This time Daryl Mitchell has to depart.

OUT! THREE REDS AND THE KIWIS ARE 4 DOWN! Axar Patel gets his first and Micthell does not survive this time. He takes a review along with him too. The Kiwis still 99 runs away from avoiding the follow-on. The one that goes on with the arm does the trick. It is angled in from wide of the crease. Mitchell lunges and defends but does so outside the line. He misses and gets hit on the pads. An appeal and the finger is raised. Review taken after a chat between the two batters. Replays roll in and they show that the on-field call stays.
Commentary.Howout: lbw b Axar Patel

Commentary.Commentary: Now the bumper to end! It is on the body, Nicholls ducks under it.
That is a beauty! This is has swung a long, long way! Fuller and on middle, keeps moving away. Nicholls looks to drive but is beaten.
On middle, defended. The umpire now has a chat with Siraj and he has been given FIRST OFFICIAL WARNING FOR RUNNING ONTO THE DANGER ZONE!

FOUR OVERTHROWS! Bonus runs and New Zealand will not mind one bit! Length and on off, Mitchell looks to drop and run on the off side. Iyer from point gets to the ball quickly and has a shy at the bowler's end but misses. No one backing up and it goes to the fence.
Slightly fuller and on off, this is pushed to mid off.
Angled into the pads, Mitchell looks to flick but misses to get hit on the pads.
Now the one that goes on with the arm, outside off, Nicholls looks to defend but it goes off the outer half towards point.
On middle, blocked.

Just short! That is brilliant from Gill though! Nicholls comes down the track but the length is shortened. Nicholls looks to defend, it goes off the inner half but lands short of short leg. He collects it with a dive and as he is falling on the ground, fires it at the stumps at the keeper's end. Hits but Nicholls is in.
Another one floated up on off, Nicholls lunges forward and keeps it out.
Floats it up on off, this one turns back in a little. Nicholls looks to defend, it goes off the inner half to mid-wicket.
Angled into the pads, this is worked through mid-wicket for one.
Here comes the first change as Axar Patel is brought into the attack.
Another one on a length and around off, Nicholls plays it towards the off side.
FOUR! Up and over! Lovely stroke to get off the mark! Short and outside off, Nicholls upper cuts it over the slip cordon for a boundary.
Outside off, length again. Left alone.
Good length and on off, Henry is solid in defense.

Virat Kohli decides to take the review for an LBW decision. UltraEdge confirms that there is no bat involved. Ball Tracker shows that the ball is pitching outside leg and the onfield call stands. India lose the review as well.

NOT OUT! That is pitching outside leg! India lose a review but they just had to go for it right? Kohli needed to signal the 'T' for Siraj who is putting in so much of effort and bowling so well. He steams in on his hat-trick ball. Lands it around leg and gets it to straighten. Nicholls looks to defend but misses to get hit on the pads. Siraj is down on the ground in his followthrough but is still appealing. The umpire shakes his head. After a long disucssion, India review but replays show that the on-field call stays.
Henry Nicholls comes in to face the Hat-Trick delivery.

OUT! TIMBER! Siraj, you beauty! What a delivery, what a delivery, just unplayable and Siraj is breathing fire here. He has his third and things falling apart a little too quickly for the Kiwis. He steams in and lands it on a length around middle and off. This lands and then straightens. Taylor plays down the wrong line. It goes past the outside edge and uproots the off pole. He is on a hat-trick.
Commentary.Howout: b Mohammed Siraj

Commentary.Commentary: A length ball, on off. Daryl Mitchell defends it off the front foot. Another eventful over comes to an end.
Drifting onto the pads, Ross Taylor flicks it towards fine leg for a single.
Angled in on middle and leg, Mitchell flicks it through mid-wicket and picks up a single.
Full and attacking the pads yet again. Daryl Mitchell looks to work it on the leg side but misses and gets hit on the pads. A stifled appeal but probably slanting down leg.

Daryl Mitchell takes the review for an LBW decision. UltraEdge confirms that there' no bat involved. Ball Tracker shows that the ball is pitching in line and hits him in line as well but is going over middle stump. Really good review from Daryl Mitchell and he survives.
