NOT OUT! That is going over! The extra bounce which is being produced of this surface has saved Daryl Mitchell! A really good review and New Zealand can breathe a sigh of a relief. Yadav on the other hand, can't believe that is going over. It is a length ball, on middle, straightens a touch. Mitchell looks to defend but plays down the wrong line, he misses and gets hit on the pads. An appeal and the finger is raised. Mitchell reviews and replays show that it is going over.
Full and attacking the toes of the batter. Daryl Mitchell manages to keep it out towards short mid on.
Ross Taylor comes in at number 4.

OUT! CAUGHT! Two wickets in the over and Mohammed Siraj is elated! Another short one, banged in around the leg stump. This one is directed right around the helmet. Tom Latham looks to take it on and get on top of the bounce but falls over a little as he connects the pull shot. The ball goes aerially straight towards the who is kept a bit deep at backward square leg and Shreyas Iyer takes the catch. Tom Latham is left in disbelief and has to make the long walk back.
Commentary.Howout: c Shreyas Iyer b Mohammed Siraj

Commentary.Commentary: A bumper now, over middle stump and at 135.7 kph. Tom Latham ducks under it.
FOUR! Cracking straight drive from Latham! On a length, on middle and Latham punches it back past the bowler and picks up a boundary.
Good-length ball, around off and angling away. Tom Latham makes an easy leave.
A bit too straight and Daryl Mitchell flicks it off the pads towards deep square leg for a single.
Daryl Mitchell comes in at number 3.

OUT! CAUGHT! Mohammed Siraj gets the early breakthrough for India! A length ball, angled into middle stump. This one just straightens a bit after pitching and Will Young gets squared up. Young pushes at it with hard hands and gets an outside edge towards second slip. Virat Kohli, over there takes a sharp catch, diving low to his right. Great start for the hosts and Will Young will be disappointed.
Commentary.Howout: c Virat Kohli b Mohammed Siraj

Commentary.Commentary: FOUR! Streaky! Yadav hurls across a fullish ball, around off. Tom Latham looks for the expansive drive but gets a thick outside edge which flies well past the slip cordon and into the third man fence.
Yadav comes from around the wicket now and delivers it on the off pole. Latham stays solid in defense.
Good-length ball, around off and angling across. Latham stands tall and guides it towards backward point.
Well bowled! Yadav pitches it up, around off and at 140 kph. The ball nips away slightly after pitching and Tom Latham makes a good leave.
On leg stump, Latham looks to flick it away but misses and gets hit high on the pads.
A length ball, on off, driven straight towards cover.
On a length, angled in around the off pole and this one straightens after pitching. Will Young looks to have a poke at it but decides against it in the end.
On top of off and kept out on the off side by Young.
FOUR! Nicely timed by Will Young. On the pads, nudged through the mid-wicket region and the ball races away into the fence.
Length again, angled into leg stump. Young looks to flick but gets an inside edge onto the pads.
Will Young gets it on the left hand and straightaway signals for the physio. The physio is out and is having a look. Hope he is fine. Young is fine and we are set to resume play.

Good-length ball, on middle and leg. Latham dabs it down towards mid-wicket and sets off for a quick run. The throw comes in at the keeper's end and hits Will Young flush on the hand. That must have hurt.
A length ball, around off and nipping away from the left-hander. Tom Latham leaves it alone.
Who will bowl from the other end? Mohammed Siraj it is.
A little wayward yet again from Yadav as another one is spilled down the leg side. No need to play at that one.
JAFFA! Slingy delivery, on off and on a nagging length. This one shapes away beautifully and whizzes past the outside edge as Young looks to block.
Pitched further up, outside off and left alone by Young.
A length ball, down the leg side yet again. Will Young looks to flick but misses.
Yadav drifts onto the pads again and Tom Latham flicks it towards fine leg for a single. New Zealand are underway with that.
Umesh Yadav starts with a good-length ball, angled down the leg side. Tom Latham lets it through to the keeper.

We are back for the chase! The umpires are out in the middle as the Indian team is seen in a huddle. The New Zealand openers, Tom Latham and Will Young take guard. Mohammed Siraj has been handed the new ball.
... The Chase ...

The New Zealand bowling was about the two left-arm spinners. Both Rachin Ravindra and Ajaz Patel took all of the 7 wickets to fall with the former taking 3 and the latter with 4. Southee too bowled his heart out but with no success. New Zealand will be mentally and physically drained. However, they now need to put in a good effort with the bat. Still around 45 overs to go in the day. The hosts bowled the Kiwis out within 29 overs in the first innings, can they do the same here or will the Kiwis show some fight?

India entered their second innings with a massive lead of 263 and the openers piled up the misery by putting up a 100-run stand. Mayank got to yet another fluent half ton. Gill and Pujara missed out on theirs by 3 runs. Kohli also could not make most of the start he got. Iyer, Axar, Saha and Jayant all came out with the intention of scoring quick runs. Axar played a superb cameo and his quick fire stand with Yadav took India's lead close to 550. Once Yadav got out though, India declared.

INDIA HAVE FINALLY DECLARED! 540 is the target for the Kiwis. Still a little more than two days to go in this game but have to say, India have batted the Kiwis out of the game. However, Ajaz Patel is once again the positive for the visitors. He leads his side off the side as he finishes with 14 in the match and records the best figures by any bowler against India in India. Quite a memorable game for him.

OUT! CAUGHT AND BOWLED! Ajaz Patel gets his 14th wicket of the Test match and that's the best ever bowling performance by any bowler against India in Test matches. Take a bow! Drifted into middle and leg, spinning away. Jayant Yadav looks to turn it on the leg side but closes the face of the bat a bit too early. The ball goes off the leading edge and Ajaz Patel takes an easy return catch. Virat Kohli decides that it's time to declare. INDIA LEAD BY 539 RUNS!
Commentary.Howout: c & b Ajaz Patel

Commentary.Commentary: On middle, blocked.
Flatter and on middle, Yadav hangs back and defends.
SIX! Yadav now joins the act! He skips down the track, does not quite get to the pitch of it but still clears long on for a biggie.
The sweep comes out now, it goes more off the top edge towards deep square leg for one.
FOUR! Hammered! Axar comes down the track and gets to the pitch of it. He smashes it down the ground to the long on fence.
Slowed up, around off. Yadav plays it with soft hands towards gully.
On the pads and nudged towards mid-wicket for a quick single.
Quicker one, on leg stump. Patel fends it away.
FOUR! Short and wide, Patel waits for it and cuts it really late and fine. The ball goes quickly pst the first slip and runs away into the fence.
SIX! On a length, on middle and turning in. Axar Patel dances down the track but doesn't quite get to the pitch of the ball. Patel still keeps his shape and hits it over the mid-wicket fence.
Ravindra comes from 'round the wicket and bowls it quicker on off stump. The ball turns back in sharply but Patel keeps it out.
On off and kept out by Yadav. End of a maiden over from Ajaz Patel.
On middle, Yadav pushes at it and almost loops it back to the bowler.
Three in a row now! Flighted ball, on off and turning away sharply. Jayant Yadav is comprehensively beaten.
And again! On a length, around middle. Jayant Yadav goes on the back foot but gets beaten yet again.
Beaten! Tossed up, around middle. This one turns and bounces. Yadav looks to block but gets beaten on the outside edge.
Floated up, on off and kept out by Yadav.
SIX! Another one! Full and wide, Patel whacks it over the long off fence for yet another maximum.
Quicker one, on off and angled in. Patel keeps it out off the back foot.
SIX! Huge-hit! Tossed up, outside off. Axar Patel skips down the track, gets to the pitch of the ball and smokes it with the spin. The ball sails way over the long on fence.
FOUR! Dragged down, on middle and spinning in. Axar Patel rocks back and pulls it powerfully past the short leg fielder and into the fence.

OUT! TAKEN! Rachin Ravindra gets his third wicket and Wriddhiman Saha has to depart. Saha went for one too many and paid the price. Tossed up, on a length, around middle and leg. With the ball turning away, Saha looks to lift it against the spin. The ball goes high and behind mid on. Kyle Jamieson back-paddles and takes a fine catch. Also, Jayant Yadav walks out to bat.
Commentary.Howout: c Kyle Jamieson b Rachin Ravindra

Commentary.Commentary: Around off and spinning away. Saha manages to keep it out off the back foot.
On middle and defended out.
On a length, around off and turning in. Patel dabs it down towards short leg.
SIX! High and handsome! Tossed up, on off. Axar Patel skips down the track and hits it with the spin as he clears the wide long on fence with ease. The lead is over 500 now.
Flatter one, on off and pushed towards mid on.
Around off and this is driven through covers for a couple.
Slowed up, on off and Patel plays it with soft hands back onto the deck.
Well bowled, On off and kept out by Saha.
FOUR! Up and over! On middle, Saha gets down on one knee and swings against the turn. He gets a good connection and the ball ends up in the vacant mid-wicket fence.
On middle and leg, flicked away towards square leg for a single.
Gives it a bit more air and bowls it on off. Patel watchfully keeps it out on the leg side.
A skidder, on middle and pushed towards short mid on.
Tossed up, on off and turning in. Patel nudges it towards short mid on.
On middle and leg, defended out.
Tossed up, around off. Wriddhiman Saha steps out and looks to go aerial on the leg side but gets a leading edge. Luckily for him, the ball goes just over cover-point and they take two.
On middle, kept out.
Doesn't carry! On middle and truning away. Saha pushes at it with hands as the outside edge is found but it is short of the first slip fielder.
Loopy delivery, drifted into off stump. Saha paddles it behind square and picks up a couple.
Fuller one, on off and kept out on the off side.
FOUR BYES! This one went through everyone. On middle and the ball spins in sharply off a foot mark and goes down the leg side, past the keeper and leg slip. The ball races away into the fence.
Tossed up, on off and defended back to the bowler.
Flatter one, turning into the pads and dabbed down on the leg side.
Very full, on off and pushed towards mid off.
Quicker one, on middle and spinning down the leg side. Patel leaves it alone.
Axar Patel comes out to bat now.

OUT! Dragged on! Virat Kohli is left in disbelief as he chops it on. Rachin Ravindra bowls it a bit short and wide, spinning away. Virat Kohli looks to cut it off the back foot but doesn't quite rock back into the correct position to play the shot. In the end, he is left fetching for it a bit and the ball comes off the bottom edge and goes on to hit the off stump. New Zealand get two quick wickets and they will be a bit relieved now.
Commentary.Howout: b Rachin Ravindra

Commentary.Commentary: Rachin Ravindra comes from the opposite end now.
FOUR! Swept and done so nicely! On middle, this is played through square leg. Boundary.
On the pads, this is worked through square leg for one.
On middle, defended.
Saha is off the mark! On off, this is pushed through covers for one.
Wriddhiman Saha comes in at number 6.

The umpires have gone upstairs for a stumping chance. The catch will also be checked. UltraEdge shows there's no spike. The stumping on the other hand, looks really close. Iyer's foot is planted firmly on the line, the question is whether there is anything behind the line. This one is a real hair-scratcher for the third umpire. The third umpire concludes that no part of the foot is behind the popping crease and OUT is the decision on the big screen.

OUT! STUMPED! Iyer has nothing behind the crease and that is probably the right decision. Ajaz Patel strikes again. What a game this guy is having. What a beauty of a delivery. It is tossed up on middle, it lands and then turns away. Iyer lunges to defend but is beaten. The keeper whips the bails off and enquired in a polite manner. It is referred and replays show that Iyer is short. Another batter comes and another goes but no declaration.
Commentary.Howout: st Tom Blundell b Ajaz Patel

Commentary.Commentary: BIG TURN! This lands on off and then spins away. Iyer is beaten as he tries to block.
Ajaz Patel (21-2-77-2) is brought back into the attack.
Down the leg side. Kohli looks to sweep but mistimes it to short fine leg.
Fuller and on middle, this is pushed down to long on for one.
On middle, this is worked to mid-wicket.
SIX! Back-to-back biggies! The message is clear now, India are going for quick runs. Once again comes down the track, this is tossed up, Iyer whips it well over the mid-wicket fence for a maximum.
SIX! Into the stands. Solid use of the feet. Steps down the track and heaves it with the spin over mid-wicket. That was just the third ball Iyer faced. He's come out with intent.
On middle, defended.
On off, this is pushed to covers.
Iyer is off the mark as he works it through square leg.

DRINKS! Virat Kohli and Shubman Gill came out post Lunch and looked positive as they kept on using their feet and putting the bad balls away. William Somerville has been put under immense pressure but Rachin Ravindra has bowled better and just sent Gill back to the pavilion before the interval, who was batting on 47. Can the visitors get a few quick wickets now? Also, Shreyas Iyer walks out to bat.

OUT! TAKEN! Stop the press, finally, someone other than Ajaz Patel has taken a wicket for the Kiwis. Soft dismissal. This is short. Gill lines up to cut it but this one comes in with the angle. He then tries to push it but does so uppishly and straight into the hands of Tom Latham at covers.
Commentary.Howout: c Tom Latham b Rachin Ravindra

Commentary.Commentary: On off, kept out.
Shorter, this is pulled through mid-wicket for one.
Outside off. This stays low. Kohli is beaten as he tries to cut.
On the pads, Gill looks to defend but misses to get hit on it.
Top edge but safe! The reverse sweep comes out. Due to the extra bounce in the surface, it goes off the top edge, lands safe and rolls towards third man for two.
Flatter and on off, Kohli guides it to point for one.
On middle, this is worked through mid-wicket for no runs.
Gill comes down the track, does not get to the pitch of it and hence, he looks to drag it, it goes just over mid-wicket for one.
Tossed up outside off, defended.
Another one on the stumps, kept out.
On middle, defended.
FOUR! Up and over! This is way too short, Kohli rocks back and pulls it over mid-wicket for another boundary.

Turn, bite, bounce. That had everything. Quicker and on middle, this turns away, skids through and there is also extra bounce. Kohli goes back and tries to defend. It goes off the outside edge to point.
Outside off, left alone.
Shorter and outside off, extra bounce on this one, Kohli looks to cut as he tries to get on top of the bounce but under edges it to covers.
A single to end the over as Kohli plays this through covers.
Short and down the leg side, this is pulled to fine leg for one.
Loopy ball on middle, this is pushed to mid on.
On middle, this is worked through mid-wicket for one.
Slower through the air, outside off, Kohli looks to defend, this turns back in and goes off the inner half on the leg side.
Kohli comes down the track, the length is shortened, it is worked to mid-wicket.
On off, this is pushed to covers.
Well left! Just outside off, Gill does not fiddle with it.
Flatter and on middle, Gill hangs back and defends.
Slower and the line is just outside off, left alone.
On off, this is pushed to covers.
Outsidr off, left alone.
On a length, on off and Gill defends it off the back foot.
On off, Kohli strides forward and works it past short mid on for a single.
Tossed up, around off and defended out.
Flighted ball, on off and Kohli taps it towards short mid on.
Flatter one, on off and punched off the back foot on the off side for a run.
Spilled down the leg side and spinning further away. Gill looks to paddle but misses and the keeper does well to pouch it.
Fullish ball, on middle and leg. Gill works it with soft hands towards mid on and scampers through for a run. Good running.
Quicker one, around off and defended out.
On off and kept out by Gill.
Around off, nudged towards cover-point for a quick single. The throw at the keeper's end is a bit wild and they do get an overthrow as well.
NO BALL! On off, eased towards mid off. A no ball is called as Rachin Ravindra oversteps.
Pushed through, around off and turning away. Kohli hops back and works it towards square leg for one.
Short and wide, played to deep point for a run.
A tad bit shorter, around middle. Gill goes on the back foot and dabs it down towards backward square leg for a single.
On middle, pushed towards mid on.
Down the leg side, Gill paddles it fine and gets back for the second.
Flatter one, around middle and leg. Gill comes forward and nudges it past short leg.
FOUR! Shubman Gill gets a bit funky now. On a length, around off. Gill reverse sweeps it behind square on the off side for a boundary.
Flighted ball, on off. Gill steps out and defends it back to the bowler.
On off, defended out. Maiden over from Rachin Ravindra.
Tossed up, around off and turning away a bit. Virat Kohli puts out a stride and leaves it alone.
A touch short and wide, cut away to cover.
On middle and driven towards mid on.
Pushed through, outside off. Kohli goes on the back foot and works it towards cover.
Dragged down, around off and pulled straight to mid on.
Shouts of 'Catch it' but its well wide of short leg. On a length, around off and turning in. Gill strides out to defend but gets an inside edge onto the pads and just wide of short leg.
On middle, pushed down the ground for a single. It's pretty easy out there for the Indian batters at the moment.
SIX! All the way! Somerville tosses it up, outside off. Virat Kohli skips down the track and uses his wrists to slog it away, well over the mid-wicket fence for a biggie.
Floated up, on middle. Shubman Gill uses his feet to ease it down to long on for a single.
FOUR! On off and Gill slogs it away with the turn and finds the mid-wicket fence.
On a length, outside off and turning in. Gill puts out a stride and pads it away on the off side.
Tossed up, outside off and Kohli defends it towards cover.
On the pads and nudged towards mid-wicket for one.
Ravindra gives it a bit more air and bowls it on off stump. Gill watchfully keeps it out.
On a nagging length, around middle and turning away. Gill goes on the back foot to defend.
Fired in at leg stump. Gill jams it out on the off side.
Flatter one, angled into middle and leg. Kohli pushes it out on the leg side for a run.
Slowed up and bowled on off stump. Gill keeps it out.

SIX! Just over! Nicely tossed up, on off. Shubman Gill skips down the track and lifts it really high towards the cow corner fence. The fielders from deep mid-wicket and long on converge but can't get to it as the ball sails over the fence.
Fullish ball, on off and driven through mid on for a single.
Slightly shorter, outside off and turning in. VK gets right behind the line of the ball.
Looped up, on off and Kohli drives it off the inner half of the bat towards mid off.
Floated up, around off. Shubman Gill uses his feet to push it towards long on for one.
On off and punched down towards long off for a single.
Nicely bowled again! Tossed up, on off and allowing the ball to do the job. Kohli strides forward but gets another outside edge, past first slip. They take a single.
Around off, defended out.

That one just popped up off the surface! On a length, around off and the ball hits a crack and takes off as it spins away. Virat Kohli is take by surprise as he gets a thick edge towards short third man. They come back for two.
On off and kept out on the off side.
Nicely bowled! Floated up, around off and this one turns away nicely. Virat Kohli presses forward to push at it but gets beaten on the outside edge.
Who will bowl from the other end? Rachin Ravindra it is.
On a length, around off and turning in. VK goes on the back foot and works it towards square leg for a single.
On middle again and kept out on the leg side.
On middle and leg, turning in. Kohli looks to turn it on the leg side but pads it just short of short leg.
Very full, around middle. Kohli jams it out towards mid on.
A touch fuller, around off and driven towards short mid off.
Tossed up, on middle. Kohli nudges it towards short leg.
We are back for the post Lunch session! Shubman Gill and Virat Kohli stride out to the middle. William Somerville to start proceedings with the ball after the interval.
... Day 3, Session 2 ...

The story is the same for the Kiwis. It is Ajaz who is picking wickets at one end and Southee keeping it tight at the other. They need more from the others. They would be eager to get India all out so that they don’t have to spend a lot of time in this heat. Will there be a fightback from them in the next session?

India continue to pile on the misery on the Kiwis. It was Mayank and Pujara who started the day well. Mayank got to his half ton, before the two fell in quick succession to Ajaz Patel. Now Kohli and Gill are amidst another strong stand. The lead is already one which we believe is enough, how much more will India want?
Tossed up on off. Shubman Gill pushes it to the fielder at short extra cover. So India are 142/2 on Lunch on day 3 of this Test match.
Quicker again outside off and turns away sharply. Gill decides to leave it alone.
Quicker again on off. Gill defends this out.
This is dragged down short but stays low. Kohli pulls it to square leg for a single.
Tossed up on middle. Kohli pushes it back to the bowler.
Quicker through the air on middle. Kohli blocks it out.
Rachin Ravindra (1-0-4-0) comes into the attack now.
Shorter length again. Gill gets back and defends it comfortably.
Short ball on off this time. Kohli pulls it infront of square and gets a single towards the fielder at cow corner.
On a length, on middle. Kohli works it to square leg.
On a length, on the pads. Kohli looks to tuck it away but gets rapped up on thigh. The ball deflects towards the on side.
Short ball this time on leg. Virat Kohli decides to let it go.
On the pads and Gill tucks it to long leg for a single.
Tossed up on middle. Kohli blocks it out.
On middle and leg, Worked towards the on side for a single.
Shorter length this time on middle. Virat Kohli uses his wrists and works it towards the deep mid-wicket region. Theey run three. Good running by the Indian batters.

TWO BYES! Ajaz Patel has bowled three absolute world class deliveries. Tossed up, around the off stump, allowing the ball to do its bit. The ball grips, bounces and turns away sharply. Virat Kohli is comprehensively beaten and the extra bounce deceives the keeper as well as it goes through him. The batters take a couple of byes and the ball goes towards third man.

Review time! Out of nowhere, just as the timer runs out, Tom Latham decides to take the review for an LBW decision. This one is quite similar to the one that got Kohli in the first innings. UltraEdge shows that there is a clear deflection off the bat this time and the original decision stays. New Zealand lose a review as well.

NOT OUT! Tossed up again on off and this one seems to be going on with the arm. Virat Kohli looks to defend it but gets the inside edge of his blade onto the pads. There is an appeal for LBW. But the umpire says no. They take a review and replays roll in. UltraEdge shows huge spike off the blade and the decision stays not out.
What a ball! Tossed up on leg, The ball turns away sharply and beats the outside edge of his blade. The ball hits his pads and goes towards the fielder.
Shorter length again on middle. Gill just backs away a little and taps it towards the off side.
Length ball, on the pads. Gill tucks it to square leg.
He connects the pull this time! Short ball again on off. Kohli pulls it to fine leg for a single.
Another short delivery around leg. Virat Kohli looks to pull this time but misses.
Short ball again but down the leg side this time. Kohli leaves it alone.
Short ball on middle from 'round the wicket. Kohli pulls it well but straight to the square leg fielder.
On middle and Kohli turns it away to mid-wicket with his strong wrists. Rachin Ravindra does well there and keeps it to just a single.
Tossed up on off. Gill drives it to long off for a single.
An arm ball this time. Gill gets back and punches it square on the off side.
Slower in the air on middle this time. Gill defends this off the front foot.
Tossed up delivery again on middle. Pushed to covers this time.
Tossed up on middle. Gill skips down the track and pushes it back to the bowler.
On a length and around off this time. Kohli pushes it off the front foot towards point.
A length delivery on middle. Kohli blocks it off the front foot.
Short ball from 'round the wicket. Gill pulls it to long leg for another single.
A length ball, on middle. Worked towards deep square leg for a single.
On a length and angling into off. Kohli gets back and defends it.
On a length, on off. Kohli defends this off the front foot towards the off side.
Shorter length and outside off. Gill cuts it to point.
Tossed up on off. Defended off the front foot by Gill.
Shorter length outside off this time. Kohli slaps it towards covers. The fielder there misfields and give away a single.
Quicker on off. Blocked off the front foot.
Tossed up on off. Defended off the front foot.
Ohh...turn and bounce! Tossed up on off. Kohli looks to defend it but the ball beats the outside edge of his blade as it turns away.
FOUR! Short ball outside off this time. Shubman Gill backs away and slaps it wide of the diving mid off fielder for a boundary.
Short ball from 'round the wicket this time. Gill looks to pull it first but then keeps his bat there. The ball hits right at the top of his handle and goes behind square on the on side.
On a length directing towards middle and leg. Kohli clips it to deep square leg for a single.
Shorter length, on off. Kohli drops it towards the on side with soft hands.
Another one drifting down the leg. Virat Kohli looks to work it away but it is way down the leg side.
Drifting down the leg side. Kohli looks to flick it but misses.
Floated up on off, kept out.
Run out appeal! It is taken upstairs. Kohli seems in.
NOT OUT! On off, this is pushed back to the bowler. Ajaz gets cheeky as he back flicks it onto the stumps at his end. An appeal and it is referred but replays show that Kohli is in.
Loopy ball, extra bounce on this one. Defended.
Outside off, this is played through point for one.
On off, defended.
On off, this is pushed down to long off for one.
On middle and leg, worked towards mid on.
Good-length ball, around off and Kohli presses forward to defend it out.
Short again, down the leg side and guided down to fine leg for a single.
Short again, this time Gill gets cramped for room as he manages to dab it down on the leg side.
A length ball, around off and angling away. Left alone by Gill.
FOUR! Short ball, around leg stump. Shubman Gill makes room and pulls it through mid-wicket and picks up a boundary.
On off, punched towards mid off.
Virat Kohli walks out to bat now.

OUT! TAKEN! Ajaz Patel with yet another wicket in this Test match. Nicely tossed up, on off stump and the ball grips and turns away. Cheteshwar Pujara presses forward looking to block it but ends up getting a slight feather on it. The ball goes towards first slip, where Ross Taylor takes a fine low catch. The umpires do go upstairs wanting to make sure it's a clean catch and after having a good look at it, the third umpire decides that the fingers were underneath the ball. Cheteshwar Pujara has to depart after a positive outing.
Commentary.Howout: c Ross Taylor b Ajaz Patel

Commentary.Commentary: Has that been taken cleanly? The umpires have gone upstairs to check. Yes, it has been taken cleanly as shown in the replay. The shadows made it a bit difficult to judge but there's conclusive evidence that Taylor's fingers were under the ball.
Fuller one, on middle and pushed towards short mid-wicket.
Drifted into the pads and then turning away. Pujara plays it with soft hands on the leg side.
On middle, eased down towards mid on for a single.
On a length, around middle and pushing the batter back. Gill dabs it down towards short leg.
Another short one to finish. This is on middle and goes over the off stump. Pujara yet again just ducks under it.
On a length, around off and angling across. Pujara keeps it out towards short mid off.
Shorter in length again, going over the middle stump. Pujara gets really low to let it through to the keeper.
Another bumper, around leg stump. Pujara ducks under it.
LEG BYE! Well-directed short ball, at the body. Gill manages to keep it down behind short leg, off the hips and picks up a leg bye.
A length ball, down the leg side. Gill shuffles across a bit looking to pull but the ball goes off the thigh pads and into the keeper's mitts.

DRINKS! India continue to strengthen their hold on this game. Mayank and Pujara started off nicely and took the lead over 350. Ajaz Patel though has gotten the sole wicket for the Kiwis and since then, the Kiwis have a different energy about them. They though will hope for a few more wickets quickly. India on the other hand, will just keep batting.

NOT OUT! What a fantastic review from Cheteshwar Pujara! This is looked out from the naked eye but Pujara survives. Tossed up, on off and turning away slightly. Pujara strides out to defend but gets rapped on the pads. Ajaz Patel appeals and the umpire raises his finger. The review is taken and UltraEdge confirms that there's no bat involved. Ball Tracker shows that it's pitching in line, the impact is in line but it was just spinning enough to miss the off stump.
On off and kept out.

What happened here! Shorter in length, around middle and turning away. Pujara rocks back, looking to pull but the ball holds a bit in the surface. Pujara is halfway through his shot as the ball goes off the toe end towards slip.
Tossed up, on off. Pujara skips down the track and pushes it through the cover region for a couple.
A touch short and wide, turning away. Gill reaches out and slaps it towards point where Somerville makes a good stiop. Single taken.
Around off, Gill looks to block but gets an outside edge which doesn't carry to first slip.
Yet another short one, Gill pulls it down to fine leg for one.
One more short ball on the body, Gill ducks.
Bangs it short and on the body. Gill looks to pull but misses to get hit on the body.
Shorter and on the body, this is worked on the leg side for one.
On off, Pujara pushes it to mid off.
A bumper, ducked under.
An apples but turned down. This lands outside leg. It holds its line. Full leaves it alone. It hits the glove and the pad as Gill tries to pad it away.
A single now as this is pushed wide of long off.
On middle, kept out nicely.
All of a sudden something is happening now. This lands on leg and turns away sharply. Pujara looks to flick, it goes off a soft leading edge on the off side.
Shubman Gill comes in at number 3.

OUT! TAKEN! Agarwal holes out! 11th wicket in the game for Ajaz Patel and New Zealand finally manage to get a breakthrough. It is tossed up. Agarwal comes down the track again and looks to go over long off this time. The ball though just turns a bit and hence, it is more off the outer half. Young at long off moves to his left and takes it. Another classy innings by Agarwal. Kiwis will hope this opens the floodgates.
Commentary.Howout: c Will Young b Ajaz Patel

Commentary.Commentary: FOUR! Glorious! He is a top player of spin. Lovely use of the feet, makes room and lifts it over covers for a boundary.
Two to end the over. This time he goes full and on middle, it is clipped through mid-wicket for two.
This time it is down the leg side. Left alone.
Another short one, does not quite bounce a lot. Blocked.
Another short delivery around middle and leg. Cheteshwar Pujara sways away from the line of the ball.
Extra effort on this delivery. It is on the body, extra bounce. Pujara does well to play it by taking a hand off the handle.
Short and on the body, this is nudged to mid-wicket.
Slows it up and lands it on off, Agarwal plays it to covers.

PUT DOWN! That had to stick. It came back like a rocket. Agarwal steps out and makes it into a half volley. He drills it back towards the bowler who sticks his right hand out but the ball bursts through and rolls towards mid on.
Slower through the air and on middle, defended with a big stride forward.
Angled into the pads, skids through, Agarwal goes back and blocks.
Another one which is on the stumps, defended.
On middle, blocked.
Outside off, shorter, left alone.
Another one which is banged short. Left alone.
Yet another short one, Pujara lets it go over him.
Yet another short one on the body, it is nudged on the leg side for one.
On the body, Agarwal hops and blocks.
Mayank Agarwal gets a blow on the right arm and seems to be in a bit of pain. The physio is out on the pitch and is having a look. Everything seems to be fine now and Agarwal is good to go.

Short and on the body, Agarwal at first wanted to move out of the way. He then realised he's too late for it and ends up mistiming his pull on the leg side. It actually came off the glove and Agarwal is in pain.
Back-to-back maidens for New Zealand. On middle and defended out.
Beaten! Nicely tossed up, on off and turning away sharply. Cheteshwar Pujara looks to block it but the ball goes past the outside edge.
Quicker one, outside off stump and going on with the arm. Cheteshwar Pujara pads it away.
On the pads, kept out towards short leg.
On a length, on off and punched towards long off for an easy single. The 100 is up for India.
Drifting onto middle stump. Agarwal gets an inside edge onto the pads as he looks to defend.
Another short ball to end the over. Angled towards the body from around the leg stump and Pujara ducks under it. A maiden over for Tim Southee.
Shorter in length, on leg stump and angling across. This time Pujara hops and defends it well.
Another short ball, at the body. Cheteshwar Pujara hops to sway away from it but gets hit on the back this time.
Back of a length, down the leg side and left alone.

That seemed a bit nasty! Another bouncer, around leg stump and angled towards the body. Pujara sways away from it and thankfully gets hit on the arm guard, otherwise, the ball would have crashed right into the elbow.
A bumper from around the wicket and this one is over the leg stump. Cheteshwar Pujara ducks down and let's it through.
Flighted delivery, on off and blocked out with ease by Agarwal.
Around off and nudged away towards point.
Flatter delivery, on middle. Agarwal defends it off the back foot.
Patel gives it a bit more air and drifts it into middle and leg. Agarwal strides out to defend.
FOUR! Pushed through quicker, on off. Mayank Agarwal thrashes it uppishly through the cover region for another boundary.
SIX! Yet another half-century for Mayank Agarwal. He's just growing in confidence now. Tossed up, around off and Agarwal skips down the track to lift it well over the extra cover fence for a biggie.
On top of off, defended out by Pujara.

A well-directed bouncer from Tim Southee, right around the helmet. Mayank Agarwal looks to hook but is not in control of the shot as the ball goes aerially behind square on the leg side. The fielder from deep square leg runs around to cut it off and keeps it to three.
Full, on off and blocked out.
Review! Mayank Agarwal seems confident as he takes the review for an LBW decision right away. UltraEdge confirms that the ball just got the inside edge and the decision will now be reversed. NOT OUT!

NOT OUT! Excellent review from Mayank Agarwal and he knew that he hit it. A length ball, on middle and slanting in sharply. Agarwal looks to tuck it away but gets rapped on the pads. The visitors appeal and the finger is raised. Agarwal reviews and UltraEdge confirms that there was bat involved. Mayank Agarwal survives and Tim Southee is left a little frustrated.
Pitched up, well outside off and left alone by Agarwal.
A good bouncer, over off stump. Mayank Agarwal sways his head away from it.
Slowed up, around middle and leg. Pujara nudges it on the leg side.
Very full, on middle and pushed towards mid off.
Tossed up, on off. Pujara skips down the track and pushes it to mid off.
FOUR! Shorter in length, on off. Cheteshwar Pujara uses the depth of the crease well and lifts it over mid-wicket and collects yet another boundary. Ajaz Patel being put under pressure here.
Tossed up, around off and spinning away. Pujara shows a pad at it but the ball goes through to the keeper.
Floated up, on middle. Cheteshwar Pujara strides forward to defend.
Length again, on off and defended out by Agarwal.
Pitched up, on off and angling in. Agarwal leans forward and drives it nicely towards mid off.
FOUR! Southee strays onto the pads and gets punished. Fullish ball, down the leg side and Agarwal flicks it away into the fine leg fence.
Slightly fuller, on off and kept out on the off side.
Angled into middle and leg, nudged towards mid-wicket.

Just short! Southee starts off with a length ball, around off stump. Mayank Agarwal doesn't move his feet as he gets squared up. The ball goes off the outside edge and falls short to the right of Ross Taylor at second slip, who does manage to get a hand to it.
Who will bowl from the other end? It's going to be Tim Southee.
FOUR! And again! Very full, around the pads and Pujara works it through the huge gap at mid-wicket and picks up another boundary.
FOUR! Positive intent from the get go from Cheteshwar Pujara. Flighted, on middle and leg, Pujara comes down the track and clips it through mid-wicket for a boundary.
Slowed up, on a length and outside off. The ball turns away as Pujara taps it to cover-point.
On off and punched down towards long off for a single.
On middle, pushed back to the bowler.
Uppish but safe! Tossed up, around middle and inviting the drive. Mayank Agarwal goes for it but hits it just wide of short cover.

We are ready for play! The umpires are out in the middle and so are the New Zealand players. The overnight batters for India, Mayank Agarwal and Cheteshwar Pujara take guard. Ajaz Patel to start proceedings with the ball.

Murali Kartik and Deep Dasgupta are pitchside. They say that 16 wickets fell on Day 2 and the pitch is not necessarily a spinner's paradise right now and there aren't any demons in the pitch itself. The best way to counter the turn for a batter is to use his feet just like Mayank Agarwal did and unsettle the bowler. The batters will find it difficult to get going but if they spend enough time, runs can be scored.

The Kiwis, on the back of a historical bowling display from Ajaz Patel, kept the hosts to a score of under 350. Their batting though left a lot to ponder as the visitors were bundled out for just 62. Not having picked up a single Indian wicket yet in the second innings means that today could be another long and hard day for New Zealand. Can they stage a miraculous comeback? We'll have to wait and watch.

Hello and a warm welcome to Day 3 of the second Test match between India and New Zealand. Day 2 moved at rapid pace as 16 wickets fell in the day. After a mini collapse with the bat, the Indian bowlers came out with fire in their belly and put on a stunning display as they bundled out the Kiwis for their lowest Test score against India. The hosts have the match firmly in their grip as they stretched their lead to 332 runs and it'll be interesting to see how long they decide to bat as a lot of time is still left in this match.
... Day 3, Session 1 ...

For the Kiwis, it would be nothing less than a miracle if they salvage something out of this game. All they can do for now is show tremendous character and just not let India go along their merry way. They would hope to pick wickets quickly because that is the only way they would have a slender chance in this game. After the demoralizing batting effort, do they have any fight left in them? We will find out on Day 3, the action begins at (0400 GMT) 0930 local. Till then, take care and goodbye!

Mayank Agarwal is up for a quick chat. He says that it felt amazing and that innings was all about grit and determination. Adds that he did not change his technique much because it was more of a mental battle. Mentions that he needs to stay positive against the spinners, against someone like Ajaz Patel who was bowling brilliantly so it's necessary to put the other bowlers under the pump a bit. Adds that the Indian domestic circuit is very tough and one needs to apply his skills to the maximum in order to do well. Ends by saying that they will look to bat well tomorrow and set a target for the opposition.

They had the choice of enforcing the follow-on but they decided to bat yet again. The lead is now well above 300 and they have all 10 wickets in hand. Right then, it's time to unplug New Zealand's tour of India. It wasn't a fruitful one for the Kiwis after the high of the T20 World Cup but India managed to step into the Rahul Dravid era with a bang. The Indian team had issues with their batting (middle order) that they would like to sort out before their tour of South Africa. As far as New Zealand are concerned, they will return home and host Bangladesh in a Test series. The other cricketing action will continue and until we meet again, it's goodbye from us. Cheers!

Virat Kohli, the Indian captain, says it was a clinical performance, the first Test was also good but this was very clinical. States they discussed the areas where they can improve on after the first Test match but also feels that the pitch in Kanpur didn't assist the bowlers much on the final day and the New Zealand batters stuck it out. Further says that the wicket at the Wankhede Stadium had more bite and pace and assisted the bowlers. On his new alliance with Rahul Dravid, Kohli replies that the previous management did a great job and the mindset remains the same to take Indian cricket forward. Regarding the upcoming tour, Kohli says that South Africa will be a tough challenge and reminds us that on their last tour to that region, they got the mentality that they can win abroad. Feels that they are a better-experienced team now and the knowledge of the conditions will help them.

RAVICHANDRAN ASHWIN IS THE MAN OF THE SERIES! Starts by saying that he knows this is his 10th Man of the Series award in Tests. Adds that he enjoyed the wicket, it had more bite in the morning but slowed down as the game went on and run-scoring became easier in the evening. Terms it a wonderful surface and he has always loved bowling here. Credits the way Ajaz Patel bowled and it was wonderful to watch as he put the right-handers under huge pressure. Mentions that spin bowling is an art that needs evolution and time, and Axar Patel will learn a lot in due course. Mentions he is looking forward to the series in South Africa and wants a series win there. Also tells that Virat Kohli is always in good form in South Africa and he is looking forward to seeing him and Cheteshwar Pujara score runs.

MAYANK AGARWAL IS THE MAN OF THE MATCH! Says that it feels good to be back among the runs and it was a special knock. Adds that he didn't do anything different and it was all about the game plans and having mental discipline. Shares that Rahul Dravid told him not to think about the technique mid-series and stick to a solid mindset. Adds that Sunil Gavaskar advised him to try to keep his bat low in the initial period. Smiles and says that he is really happy with the performance and is looking forward to the challenge in South Africa.

Tom Latham, the captain of New Zealand, says that it was a disappointing performance and credits India for the way they played. Adds that he always knew it was going to be tough, they did well in the first Test but were poor in the second. Feels that the toss played a big role as you always want to bat first in such conditions but he is pleased with the way his bowlers toiled in the first innings. Mentions selection was tough coming into this game but that is a good thing for them. On Ajaz Patel's 10-wicket feat, Latham replies that it was a historic moment and for the whole squad, to be a part of it, was amazing. Informs that a couple of Test matches back home are lined up against Bangladesh and they will have to start preparing for it.
Presentation coming up...

Rahul Dravid, the head coach of India, comes up for a chat. Says that it's good to win the series but they had to work hard for it. Adds that there were phases when they were behind and had to fight through. Mentions that it's great to see the boys stepping up and credits them for showing up in the absence of some senior players. Praises Jayant Yadav for his bowling this morning and correcting his mistakes. He is very happy with the development of Axar Patel, especially with the bat. Tells us that the new boys are offering a lot of options to them. Regarding enforcing the follow-on, Dravid replies that they had a lot of time left in the game, so they didn't think about it, as there were youngsters in their team, and they wanted to give them the opportunity to test themselves on this pitch - things they might experience going ahead. On the selection headaches, Dravid replies that it's a very good situation to be in and tells that they have to manage the workload of their players and ensure to get their best XI. Tells that there is a great depth in the squad and there is a lot of desire. Admits that at times they will have to take tough decisions but they need to make sure to have clear communication with the players.

Rachin Ravindra and Ajaz Patel are up for a chat. The latter says it is a special occasion for him and his family and to do that in Mumbai is very special. Adds he is quite sore but he has a lot of time to recover now. Ravindra says he is delighted to share space with the great man next to him and what he did was brilliant. On being asked about the catch that gave Ajaz his 10th wicket, Rachin replies that he was very nervous under the high ball, he saw his teammates celebrating and he felt the pressure. Patel mentions he enjoyed his time here, it was about adjusting to the conditions that are quite different from home. Tells that he is very grateful for the love people have shown, it is overwhelming and it will take time to sink in.

Shreyas Iyer says that it was a memorable series for him and shares that he saw the hall of fame board at the Wankhede Stadium and his name will come there. Adds that there are so many good players around and the competition is stiff so he just needs to perform and seize the opportunity. On Rahul Dravid, Shreyas says that he is very good at giving confidence and his work ethic is great. He is very happy to be working with him. Concludes by saying that he is looking forward to a much-needed 5-day break.

Jayant Yadav starts by saying that it was a nice pitch to bowl on and the morning conditions helped. Adds that there was much more bite and they just needed to bowl in the good areas. Shares that the Wankhede Stadium has a special memory for him, he scored a hundred last time and almost got a fifer this time around. Tells that playing with Ravichandran Ashwin is great and it's useful to feed off Ashwin's mind as he thinks of the game in a different way and it's a great learning curve for him.
Jayant Yadav and Shreyas Iyer come up for a chat...

All said and done, despite the result going against New Zealand, this Test match will be best remembered for Ajaz Patel's 10-wicket haul in an innings - one of the rarest feats to achieve in cricket. In the city of dreams, a Mumbai-born man created history for New Zealand and will always cherish this Test match that etched his name in the elite company of Jim Laker and Anil Kumble.

As we mentioned, it was a tricky surface, more challenging than the one in Kanpur. The Indian batting lost path but it was Mayank Agarwal who held the fort in the first innings and through his awe-inspiring knock and handy contributions from the lower order, India ended up getting quite a decent total. Thereafter, it was all about the Indian bowlers who dominated in the first innings with the spinners finishing things off that Mohammed Siraj started. The hosts didn't enforce the follow-on considering the challenges of batting last on this pitch and batted the second time with a lot of control. Mayank again got runs and the others also chipped in to set a hefty target of 540 runs for the Kiwis. In reply, only Daryl Mitchell and Henry Nicholls put up some kind of a fight as Ravichandran Ashwin and Jayant Yadav ruled the roost with 8 wickets combined.

It's always tough for a team to bounce back after getting shot out for just 62 in an innings of a Test match, more so, on Indian soil. New Zealand suffered that fate and were never in contention. Unlike the first Test match, their batting didn't show the same kind of spark and character when put under pressure on a tricky surface. The end result was always known once they conceded a big lead and India put out a professional bowling display to achieve victory on Day 4.

All over! That was inevitable. It was only a matter of time. India didn't waste much time in picking the remaining 5 wickets and have pocketed the series, and more importantly, added 12 points in the ICC World Test Championship 2021-23 points table to strengthen their position. Happy faces in the Indian camp, it was a very dominating performance from them as they registered their biggest win in Test cricket (by runs). Also, with that loss, New Zealand's longest unbeaten run in Tests comes to an end.

Ashwin gets his 4th and India, along with the game, win the series too.

Quicker and around leg, turn and bounce again, Rachin gets back to block but it takes his thigh pad and drops near silly point.
Lands it full and around off, skidding in, Ravindra brings his bat in front in defense.
The line moves to outside off now, a loopy delivery, turning away, Rachin covers his stumps and shoulders arms.
Another full ball, this time the line is around leg, Rachin helps it towards mid-wicket.
Fullish and around off, this time Rachin Ravindra is forward in defense and does well to block it away.
Beaten straightaway! A perfect start from Jayant. He tosses it up and lands around off, Ravindra tries to defend but the ball spins away to beat the outside edge.

All in readiness here at the Wankhede Stadium. The players have come out in the middle. Henry Nicholls and Rachin Ravindra are the overnight Kiwi batters. As expected, India will start with spin. Jayant Yadav is ready to bowl. Silly point and two slips in place. Here we go...

Pitch report - Simon Doull says that the pitch looks the same and it will offer spin and bounce. The Kiwi adds that he was very happy with the intent shown by Daryl Mitchell and Henry Nicholls. Feels that it's possible to bat on this surface by keeping positive intent and aggressive footwork.

It's a lovely morning in Mumbai, bright and sunny, so if New Zealand were hoping for some assistance from the weather gods, it's not there. The Indian players are going through their warm-up drills. Everyone is looking nice and relaxed, and Rahul Dravid is seen sharing some words with his boys.

Hello, folks! A 5-wicket formality is left on what could be the final day, if not the session, of this Test match and series. India have flexed their muscles to stamp their authority and have the Black Caps on the mat. It's now a matter of landing the knockout punch as New Zealand getting back on their feet looks highly unlikely. Still, cricket is a game of uncertainties and it has a habit of giving a reality check whenever you try to get too ahead of yourself. That record sixth wicket stand between Brendon McCullum and BJ Watling against India in 2014 is still fresh in our memories. A game that looked done and dusted on Day 4 got stretched deep into Day 5. Do New Zealand have the same fight left in them? Let's find out.
... Day 4, Session 1 ...

Now, the question is how long will India take to get the remaining wickets? A session? More than that? One thing is for sure the Kiwis won't be going down without a fight. Do join us for Day 4 at 0930 local (0400 GMT) for what could also be the last day of this Test.

Daryl Mitchell is down for a chat. He says that Agrawal set the template with the way he batted against the spinners. Adds that it is about finding ways to put pressure on the bowlers. Mentions that it is about constantly adapting to the situation and what the opposition is doing, it is always nice to spend time in the middle. He accepts that they are in a tough situation and it will be challenging from here to save this Test.

For India, it was the Ashwin show, he got three of the 5 to fall and bowled beautifully. Axar also got one. Yadav and the seamers were a tad disappointing. They could have had Nicholls too had India taken the review on Yadav's bowling. However, they will be pretty pleased with the day.

Another session which belongs to India! 4 wickets is what they got and they are just the 5 wickets away from winning this game! A very strange approach from the Kiwis in this session. They came out with fire, they looked to play shots especially, Mitchell, Taylor and Young. It did not come off that well for Young and Taylor but Mitchell played really well for his half ton. Nicholls gave him good support. Once Mitchell fell though Blundell did not last for long but Nicholls and Ravindra ensured there were no more wickets to fall.

On off and played towards point.
Quicker one, on middle and Ravindra keeps it out on the leg side.

Nicely tossed up, but well outside off. Easy leave for Henry Nicholls and its a maiden over.
Floated up, full and around middle. Henry Nicholls defends it off the front foot.

Full and wide, Rachin Ravindra drives it firmly but straight to mid off. Maiden over from Ashwin.
Around middle and leg, driven towards mid on.
Floated up, at the pads and nudged onto the leg side.
Attacking the stumps this time, Ravindra stays solid in defense.
Beaten! Slightly quicker, on a length and around leg. This one turns square and Ravindra is comprehensively beaten.
Tossed up, on middle and kept out by Ravindra.

Quicker one, on middle and leg, pushed towards mid on.
Sharp turn and bounce. Around off again and Nicholls makes another good leave.

FOUR! A touch short, on off and spinning away. Henry Nicholls rocks back and cuts it behind square for a boundary.

Fuller on off. Rachin Ravindra drives it to covers.

On off and turning away. Rachin Ravindra leaves it alone.

On middle and leg. Turned away to mid-wicket for a single.

OUT! RUN OUT! Mix-up there in the middle and Tom Blundell pays the price! Tossed up on off. Tom Blundell drives it to mid off and sets off for a single. Henry Nicholls sents him back as there is no run there. Tom Blundell tries to go back but throw from the substitute fielder, Srikar Bharat is accurate and Wriddhiman Saha whips the bails off as Tom Blundell is short of his crease.One wicket brings two and New Zealand have lost half of their side now.
Commentary.Howout: run out (sub Srikar Bharat / Wriddhiman Saha)

Quicker and flatter on middle. Tom Blundell gets well forward to defend it.

Quicker on middle. Defended off the front foot towards the on side.
Carrom ball this time and outside off. Henry Nicholls looks to push at it but misses.
Fuller on off. Defended off the front foot.

OUT! CAUGHT! Daryl Mitchell is gone now! He tries to play the same shot like the previous one but miscues this time and pays the price! Slower in the air on off by Axar Patel. Daryl Mitchell skips down the track and tries to go downtown again. But miscues this time. He gets it off the bottom of his blade towards deep extra-cover fielder. Commentary.Commentary: SIX! A clean strike by Daryl Mitchell! Tossed up on off. Daryl Mitchell skips down the track and lifts this straight down the ground for a biggie.
Quicker and on a shorter side by Axar Patel. Henry Nicholls pushes it to covers for a single.

Quicker this time on middle. Daryl Mitchell looks to defend but gets hit high on the pads.
On leg and turning into the batter. Daryl Mitchell leaves it alone.
Fuller this time. Safely defended by Daryl Mitchell.
Quicker and flatter on off. Defended off the back foot.
Tossed up on off. Daryl Mitchell nicely defends it off the front foot.

DRINKS! What no one expected has happened, as Daryl Mitchell and Henry Nicholls have applied themselves really well and have frustrated the Indian bowlers. Mitchell brought up a gritty fifty and apart from the odd ball beating the edge, these two seem comfortable. Ravichandran Ashwin has been brought back into the attack and after quite a long time, India look like taking a wicket. But will they? Or will these two see the Kiwis through to Day 4?
FOUR! Henry Nicholls gets the final ball away for the boundary! On middle and off. Henry Nicholls gets on his knees and reverse-sweeps it towards third man fence for a boundary.
Slightly quicker on off. Pushed to covers for a quick single.
Tossed up on off this time. Carefully blocked off the front foot.
Fuller on middle. Clipped to deep square leg for another single.
Shorter length and outside off this time. Pushed to deep cover for a single.
Slower in the air on off. Defended off the front foot.
Change from both ends as Axar Patel (5-0-25-0) comes back into the attack.

Another play and a miss! Tossed up again nicely on middle and leg. Henry Nicholls tries to defend it off the front foot but the ball misses the blade by whisker. Ravichandran Ashwin is getting good purchase out there.
Beautifully bowled! Tossed up on middle. Henry Nicholls presses forward to defend but the ball misses the outside edge of his blade as it turns away sharply.
Fuller on middle and leg. Clipped to mid on.
Shorter length on off and skids through. Daryl Mitchell pushes it to the off side and gets a quick single.
Ravichandran Ashwin (11-3-25-3) comes back into the attack.
Slightly shorter on middle and turning away. Henry Nicholls blocks it comfortably off the back foot.
Fuller on off. Henry Nicholls defends this off the front foot and gets the inside half of his blade towards mid-wicket.
Around off and turning away. Henry Nicholls lets it turn and taps it to point.
Quicker on off. Defended off the front foot.
FOUR! New Zealand are getting boundaries at regular intervals now! Tossed up on off. Henry Nicholls gets on his knees and sweeps it to deep square leg for a boundary.
Tossed up on off. Henry Nicholls gets forward and defends it to the off side.

NO BALL! Flighted delivery, on middle. Henry Nicholls comes down the track but gets completely undone in flight. The ball turns away and it's a difficult one for the keeper to take. Slightly flatter, on off. Daryl Mitchell bunts it on the off side and scampers through for a quick single.

Around the off pole and tailing back in. Daryl Mitchell defends it on the leg side.
Good-length ball, outside off and left alone.
Fullish ball, on middle. Daryl Mitchell gets squared up a bit but manages to fend it away.

The ball actually hit the pad first and then Ball Tracker showed three reds. Big let off for Henry Nicholls and is that the kind of luck he needs to get back in form?
Attacking the pads as this one is angled in from off stump. Mitchell does well to keep it out.
Turn, bite and bounce. Tossed up, around off and turning away sharply. Nicholls leaves it alone and Saha makes a good take. Maiden over.
Flatter one, on off, worked towards cover.
Quicker one, flighted around off and turning away sharply. Henry Nicholls makes a good leave.

Around middle and leg, nudged onto the leg side.
Fuller one, on off and kept out by Nicholls.

Back of a length, around off and angled at the body. Henry Nicholls taps it off the back foot to point.

On off, Nicholls blocks.

Down the leg side, the batter looks to flick but no connection.
On the pads, Nicholls sweeps, it goes off the inner half through backward square leg for two.
On off, defended.
On off, this is pushed towards cover for one.
Yet another floated up delivery on off, defended.

Outside off, fuller, this is driven to covers.

Good length and on the stumps now, defended.

Angled into the pads, this is worked through square leg for one.

Gives it air and lands it on middle, defended.
On middle, this is worked to mid-wicket for one.
Loopy ball on the pads, Mitchell looks to flick but misses to get hit on the pads.

Tossed up outside off, it is pushed towards cover for one.

DRINKS! India already has three and there are still 25 overs to go, you would not bet against them to get a victory here today itself. Mitchell though is playing really well. He though needs someone to give him proper support. Can Nicholls be the one? We will find out.
Another short one, outside off. Henry Nicholls goes on the back foot but can't get it past backward point.

Tossed up, on off. Henry Nicholls strides out to defend.
Flatter one, on off and punched through mid off for a run.

On off and kept out on the off side.
Slowed up, on middle and pushed back to the bowler.

Quicker one, on middle and kept out.
On off, Mitchell presses forward and gets an inside edge on the leg side for one.

On a length, around off and cut away towards point.

Ross Taylor comes in at number 4.

OUT! That is quite clearly off the glove! Kohli knew that and hence, he just reviewed it immediately. Young now walks back. That is a beauty of a delivery. Turn, bounce, just unplayable. This lands outside off, Young goes back to block, it turns back in sharply and also there is extra bounce. Goes off something to the fielder at short leg. The Indians are appealing, actually celebrating. The umpire shakes his head. Kohli reviews straightaway and it is a good review. India now 8 wickets away. Still 30 overs left in the day.

On off, blocked.

Flighted ball on off, Young defends it.
Gives it air and lands it on off, Young keeps it out.
Floats it up on off, Young defends.

Tossed up, around off and turning in. Young keeps it down towards short leg.

Siraj starts off with a bouncer, over middle and going down leg. Will Young ducks under it.
We are back for the final session on Day 3! Will Young and the new batter, Daryl Mitchell make their way out in the middle. Mohammed Siraj to continue with the ball after the Tea break.
... Day 3, Session 3 ...

New Zealand on the other hand, need to show a lot of character, the conditions are not easy but they will really need to dig in. Having already lost an early wicket, they have to show their skills. Can they manage to win a session, will we have a Day 4? We will find out.

Yet another session which has belonged to the Indians! Not only did they take their lead close to the 550 run mark but have also got the wicket of Latham. That is just what they would have wanted in the little time they had to bowl before Tea. More of the same is what they would want. The wicket is turning, bouncing and you would not put it against India to get all the remaining wickets today itself.
There is some issue with the spider cam and it is stuck pretty low, around the head height. The issue will take some time to get fixed and hence the umpires decide to go for the Tea break.

OUT! LBW! Down goes the first wicket and Ravichandran Ashwin gives India the perfect start. This is nicely drifted into middle and leg and this one goes on with the angle a bit. The finger is raised. Tom Latham plays for the spin but misses and gets rapped on the pads. Latham does review it but UltraEdge shows there's no bat involved and Ball Tracker comes up with three reds. The Kiwi skipper departs early yet again and New Zealand right on the back foot now. NZ also lose a review.
